"For two capacitors in series: 1/C_eq = 1/C₁ + 1/C₂ = 1/4 + 1/4 = 2/4 = 1/2. So C_eq = 2 μF. For two equal capacitors in series, the equivalent capacitance is always half of each individual capacitance.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["series combination", "equivalent capacitance", "equal capacitors"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-02", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "8 μF", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2 μF", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "4 μF", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "16 μF", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "8 μF is the result of adding the capacitances directly. This is the parallel combination formula, not the series one.", "misconception": "Using parallel formula (addition) for series combination"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "4 μF is the individual capacitance. In series, the equivalent is always less than the smallest individual capacitance.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "16 μF has no physical basis from the correct series or parallel formulas for these values.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a series combination of capacitors, which quantity remains the same across all capacitors?", "explanation": "In a series combination of capacitors, the same charge Q flows through each capacitor because they share the same current path. The charge on each capacitor is the same, while the voltage divides among them inversely proportional to their capacitances.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["series combination", "charge conservation", "constant charge"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-03", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Charge", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Potential difference", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Energy stored", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Electric field", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "In series, the total voltage divides among the capacitors. Each capacitor has V = Q/C, which differs if capacitances differ.", "misconception": "Confusing series with parallel where voltage is constant"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Energy stored U = Q²/(2C) differs for capacitors of different capacitances even though Q is the same.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Electric field depends on plate separation and voltage, which vary between capacitors in series if they have different dimensions.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Three capacitors of capacitances 2 μF, 3 μF, and 4 μF are connected in a triangular (delta) configuration between three terminals A, B, and C (2 μF between A-B, 3 μF between B-C, 4 μF between A-C). The equivalent capacitance between terminals A and B is:", "explanation": "In the delta configuration, the 3 μF (B-C) and 4 μF (A-C) are in series between A and B (through C): C_series = (3 × 4)/(3 + 4) = 12/7 μF. This series combination is in parallel with the 2 μF (directly between A-B): C_eq = 2 + 12/7 = 14/7 + 12/7 = 26/7 μF ≈ 3.71 μF.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["delta configuration", "series-parallel reduction", "equivalent capacitance"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-04", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "9 μF", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "12/7 μF", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2 μF", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "26/7 μF", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "9 μF = 2 + 3 + 4 would result from adding all three capacitances, treating them as if all were in parallel between A and B.", "misconception": "Adding all capacitances regardless of configuration"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "12/7 μF is only the series combination of the 3 μF and 4 μF through terminal C. The 2 μF directly between A and B must be added in parallel.", "misconception": "Forgetting the direct path capacitor between the terminals"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "2 μF is only the direct capacitor between A and B. The path through C also contributes to the equivalent capacitance.", "misconception": "Ignoring the series path through the third terminal"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Three capacitors of 3 μF, 6 μF, and 6 μF are connected in series. The equivalent capacitance of the combination is:", "explanation": "For series combination: 1/C_eq = 1/3 + 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6 + 1/6 + 1/6 = 4/6 = 2/3. Therefore C_eq = 3/2 = 1.5 μF. In series, the equivalent capacitance is always less than the smallest individual capacitor.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["series combination", "equivalent capacitance", "reciprocal addition"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-05", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "15 μF", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2 μF", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.5 μF", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "3 μF", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "15 μF = 3 + 6 + 6 is the parallel combination, not the series combination.", "misconception": "Using parallel formula instead of series formula"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "2 μF would result from an error in the reciprocal addition. Check: 1/3 + 1/6 + 1/6 = 4/6, giving C_eq = 6/4 = 1.5 μF.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "3 μF is the smallest individual capacitance. The series equivalent must be less than this value.", "misconception": "Thinking the equivalent equals the smallest capacitor"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A 4 μF capacitor is charged to 100 V and a 2 μF capacitor is charged to 200 V. They are then connected with plates of opposite polarity together. The common potential after connection is:", "explanation": "Q₁ = C₁V₁ = 4 × 100 = 400 μC, Q₂ = C₂V₂ = 2 × 200 = 400 μC. Since opposite plates are connected, the charges oppose each other: Q_net = Q₁ − Q₂ = 400 − 400 = 0 μC. Common potential V = Q_net/(C₁ + C₂) = 0/(4 + 2) = 0 V.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["charge redistribution", "opposite polarity", "common potential"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-06", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0 V", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "50 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "100 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "200/3 V", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "50 V would result from averaging the voltages, which is not how charge redistribution works.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "100 V would result from ignoring the opposite polarity connection and just using the first capacitor''s voltage.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "200/3 V would be the common potential if the capacitors were connected with same polarity (Q_total = 800 μC, V = 800/6).", "misconception": "Forgetting to account for opposite polarity connection"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A capacitor of 5 μF is charged to 100 V using a battery. The battery is then disconnected and a dielectric slab of dielectric constant K = 5 is inserted to completely fill the space between the plates. The final voltage across the capacitor is:", "explanation": "When the battery is disconnected, the charge Q remains constant. Q = CV = 5 × 10⁻⁶ × 100 = 500 μC. After inserting the dielectric, C'' = KC = 5 × 5 = 25 μF. New voltage V'' = Q/C'' = 500/25 = 20 V. The voltage decreases by a factor of K.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["dielectric insertion", "battery disconnected", "voltage change"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-07", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "100 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "20 V", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "500 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "50 V", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "100 V would be the voltage only if the battery were still connected. With battery disconnected, Q is constant and V changes.", "misconception": "Confusing battery-connected and battery-disconnected scenarios"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "500 V = KV would mean voltage increases with dielectric, which contradicts the physics. The dielectric reduces the field and hence the voltage.", "misconception": "Multiplying voltage by K instead of dividing"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "50 V = V/2 would result from using K = 2 instead of K = 5.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A parallel plate capacitor of capacitance C is connected to a battery of EMF V. With the battery still connected, a dielectric slab of dielectric constant K is inserted between the plates. The charge on the capacitor becomes:", "explanation": "When the battery remains connected, the voltage V across the capacitor stays constant. The new capacitance is C'' = KC. The new charge Q'' = C''V = KCV = KQ, where Q = CV was the original charge. So the charge increases by a factor K.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["battery connected", "dielectric insertion", "charge increase"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-08", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Q/K", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Q", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Q/K²", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "KQ", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Q/K would be the new charge if Q were constant and V changed — but with the battery connected, V is constant and Q changes.", "misconception": "Applying battery-disconnected logic to a battery-connected situation"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Q unchanged would imply the dielectric has no effect on charge, but with V constant and C increasing, Q = CV must increase.", "misconception": "Thinking charge remains constant with battery connected"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Q/K² does not follow from any standard capacitor-dielectric relationship.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Two capacitors C₁ = 3 μF and C₂ = 6 μF are connected in series across a 120 V supply. The voltage across the 3 μF capacitor is:", "explanation": "In series, the charge on both capacitors is the same. C_eq = C₁C₂/(C₁ + C₂) = 3 × 6/(3 + 6) = 18/9 = 2 μF. Total charge Q = C_eq × V = 2 × 120 = 240 μC. Voltage across C₁: V₁ = Q/C₁ = 240/3 = 80 V.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["series combination", "voltage division", "charge equality"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-09", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "40 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "60 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "80 V", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "120 V", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "40 V is the voltage across the 6 μF capacitor (V₂ = Q/C₂ = 240/6 = 40 V), not the 3 μF one.", "misconception": "Swapping voltage assignments between capacitors"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "60 V would result from dividing the total voltage equally, which only applies when both capacitors are equal.", "misconception": "Assuming equal voltage division in series regardless of capacitance values"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "120 V is the total supply voltage. In series, this divides between the two capacitors.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A capacitor of capacitance C charged to voltage V is disconnected from the battery. A dielectric of constant K is now fully inserted. The energy stored in the capacitor after inserting the dielectric is:", "explanation": "With battery disconnected, Q is constant. Original energy U = ½CV² = Q²/(2C). After dielectric: C'' = KC, Q'' = Q (constant). New energy U'' = Q²/(2C'') = Q²/(2KC) = U/K. The energy decreases by factor K because the dielectric is pulled in by the electric field, doing negative work on the external agent (or the field does positive work on the dielectric).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["energy change", "dielectric insertion", "battery disconnected"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-10", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "½KCV²", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "CV²/(2K)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "½CV²", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "½K²CV²", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "½KCV² would be the energy if the battery remained connected (V constant, C → KC). With battery disconnected, Q is constant, not V.", "misconception": "Applying battery-connected energy formula to a disconnected scenario"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "½CV² is the original energy. Energy must change when a dielectric is inserted because either V or Q changes.", "misconception": "Thinking energy remains unchanged with dielectric insertion"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "½K²CV² would result from squaring the dielectric constant, which has no basis in the correct energy formula.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Five capacitors, each of capacitance C, are connected as shown: C₁ and C₂ are in series, C₃ and C₄ are in series, and both series pairs are connected in parallel with each other and with C₅. The equivalent capacitance between the terminals is:", "explanation": "C₁ and C₂ in series: C_s1 = C/2. C₃ and C₄ in series: C_s2 = C/2. Now C_s1, C_s2, and C₅ are all in parallel: C_eq = C/2 + C/2 + C = 2C.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["series-parallel combination", "equivalent capacitance", "mixed network"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-11", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "C/5", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "5C", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "C", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "2C", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "C/5 would be the result if all five capacitors were in series, which is not the given configuration.", "misconception": "Treating a mixed series-parallel network as purely series"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "5C would be the result if all five capacitors were in parallel, which is not the given configuration.", "misconception": "Treating a mixed network as purely parallel"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "C would be the answer only if C₅ were absent and only the two series pairs were in parallel (C/2 + C/2 = C).", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A capacitor of 12 μF charged to 500 V is connected in parallel with an uncharged capacitor of 4 μF. The energy loss during the redistribution of charge is:", "explanation": "Initial charge Q = 12 × 500 = 6000 μC. Common potential V'' = Q/(C₁ + C₂) = 6000/16 = 375 V. Initial energy Uᵢ = ½ × 12 × 10⁻⁶ × 500² = 1.5 J. Final energy Uf = ½ × 16 × 10⁻⁶ × 375² = ½ × 16 × 10⁻⁶ × 140625 = 1.125 J. Energy loss = 1.5 − 1.125 = 0.375 J.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["energy loss", "charge redistribution", "parallel connection"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-12", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1.5 J", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.375 J", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.125 J", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.75 J", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "1.5 J is the total initial energy stored, not the energy lost. A significant fraction of this energy remains stored in the combined system.", "misconception": "Thinking all initial energy is dissipated"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1.125 J is the final energy stored in the combined capacitor system, not the energy lost.", "misconception": "Confusing final stored energy with energy loss"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "0.75 J = half the initial energy. The actual fraction lost depends on the ratio C₁C₂/(C₁+C₂)², not simply ½.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): In a series combination of capacitors, the capacitor with the smallest capacitance has the largest potential difference across it.\nReason (R): In a series combination, the charge on each capacitor is the same.", "explanation": "Both A and R are correct, and R explains A. In series, each capacitor has the same charge Q. Since V = Q/C, the capacitor with the smallest C will have the largest V. The constant charge condition (R) directly leads to the inverse relationship between V and C, explaining why the smallest capacitor has the largest voltage (A).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["series combination", "voltage distribution", "charge conservation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-13", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "R directly explains A: since Q is the same for all capacitors in series, V = Q/C is largest for the smallest C.", "misconception": "Not recognizing that equal charge is the fundamental cause of unequal voltage distribution"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "R is correct — charge conservation in a series circuit ensures the same charge appears on each capacitor.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A is correct — it follows directly from V = Q/C with Q being constant in series.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): When a dielectric slab is inserted between the plates of a charged capacitor connected to a battery, the energy stored in the capacitor increases.\nReason (R): The insertion of a dielectric slab decreases the electric field between the plates.", "explanation": "A is correct: with battery connected, V is constant and C increases to KC, so U = ½CV² increases to ½KCV². R is incorrect in this context: when the battery is connected, the voltage is maintained constant, so E = V/d remains the same (the battery supplies additional charge to maintain V). The electric field does not decrease when the battery stays connected.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["dielectric with battery", "energy increase", "electric field"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-14", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "R is incorrect when the battery is connected. The battery maintains constant V, so E = V/d stays the same — the field does not decrease.", "misconception": "Assuming the electric field always decreases with dielectric, regardless of battery connection"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "R is actually incorrect in this scenario. When the battery is connected, V is constant, so E = V/d is unchanged.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A is correct — with battery connected, V is constant and C increases by K, so energy U = ½CV² increases by factor K.", "misconception": "Confusing battery-connected and disconnected energy behavior"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the following capacitor combinations (Column I) with their equivalent capacitance (Column II). Each capacitor has capacitance C.\n\nColumn I:\nA. Two capacitors in series\nB. Two capacitors in parallel\nC. Three capacitors in series\nD. Three capacitors in parallel\n\nColumn II:\n1. C/2\n2. 2C\n3. C/3\n4. 3C", "explanation": "Two in series: C_eq = C/2 (A→1). Two in parallel: C_eq = 2C (B→2). Three in series: C_eq = C/3 (C→3). Three in parallel: C_eq = 3C (D→4).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["series combination", "parallel combination", "equivalent capacitance"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-15", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-1, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-1, B-4, C-3, D-2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A-2 gives 2C for two capacitors in series, but series combination always gives less than individual capacitance, not more.", "misconception": "Swapping series and parallel formulas"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A-3 gives C/3 for two capacitors in series, but the correct formula gives C/2, not C/3.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "B-4 gives 3C for two in parallel, but two identical capacitors in parallel give 2C, not 3C.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A parallel plate capacitor of capacitance C is charged to voltage V. Match the following operations (Column I) with their effects on energy stored (Column II):\n\nColumn I:\nA. Battery connected, dielectric K inserted\nB. Battery disconnected, dielectric K inserted\nC. Battery disconnected, plate separation doubled\nD. Battery connected, plate separation halved\n\nColumn II:\n1. Energy becomes U/K\n2. Energy becomes KU\n3. Energy becomes 2U\n4. Energy becomes 2U", "explanation": "Battery connected, dielectric inserted: V constant, C → KC, U = ½CV² → ½KCV² = KU (A→2). Battery disconnected, dielectric inserted: Q constant, C → KC, U = Q²/(2C) → Q²/(2KC) = U/K (B→1). Battery disconnected, separation doubled: Q constant, C → C/2, U = Q²/(2C) → Q²/(2·C/2) = Q²/C = 2U (C→3). Battery connected, separation halved: V constant, C → 2C, U = ½CV² → ½(2C)V² = 2U (D→4).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["energy changes", "battery connected vs disconnected", "dielectric and separation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-16", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A-1 gives U/K for battery connected with dielectric. But with battery connected, V is constant and C increases, so energy increases to KU.", "misconception": "Confusing battery-connected and battery-disconnected energy changes"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "C-4 and D-3 swap the energy doubling scenarios. Check which variable (Q or V) is constant in each case.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A-3 and B-4 do not correspond to any standard result for dielectric insertion scenarios.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The equivalent capacitance of capacitors connected in parallel is always greater than the largest individual capacitance in the combination.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. In a parallel combination, C_eq = C₁ + C₂ + C₃ + ... Since each capacitance is positive, the sum is always greater than any individual term. This is because parallel connection provides more surface area for charge storage.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["parallel combination", "equivalent capacitance", "property"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-17", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Since C_eq = C₁ + C₂ + ... and all terms are positive, the sum must exceed any individual term. The statement is true.", "misconception": "Confusing parallel combination property with series (where C_eq < smallest C)"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "When a dielectric slab is removed from a charged capacitor that is still connected to a battery, the charge on the capacitor increases.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. When the dielectric is removed with the battery connected, the capacitance decreases from KC to C (since C = ε₀A/d). With V constant (battery connected), Q = CV decreases as C decreases. The charge decreases, not increases.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["dielectric removal", "battery connected", "charge change"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-18", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Removing the dielectric decreases C. With battery connected (V constant), Q = CV also decreases. The charge does not increase.", "misconception": "Thinking dielectric removal increases charge when battery is connected"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A 6 μF capacitor and a 3 μF capacitor are connected in series across a 180 V supply. The charge on each capacitor is _____ μC.", "explanation": "For series combination, C_eq = (6 × 3)/(6 + 3) = 18/9 = 2 μF. The charge on each capacitor in series is the same and equals Q = C_eq × V = 2 × 180 = 360 μC.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["series combination", "charge calculation", "equal charge"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-19", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "180", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "540", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "360", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "1080", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "180 μC would result from using C_eq = 1 μF, which is not the correct series equivalent of 6 μF and 3 μF.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "540 μC would result from using C_eq = 3 μF instead of 2 μF, indicating an error in the series formula.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "1080 μC = 6 × 180, which would be the charge if only the 6 μF capacitor were directly connected to 180 V without the series combination.", "misconception": "Using individual capacitance instead of equivalent capacitance"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-dielectric", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A physics teacher demonstrates charge redistribution using two capacitors. She charges a 10 μF capacitor to 300 V using a battery and then disconnects it. She then connects this charged capacitor to an uncharged 20 μF capacitor.\n\nThe common potential and the ratio of final energies stored in the 10 μF and 20 μF capacitors are:", "explanation": "Initial charge Q = 10 × 300 = 3000 μC. Common potential V'' = Q/(C₁ + C₂) = 3000/(10 + 20) = 100 V. Energy in 10 μF: U₁ = ½ × 10 × 10⁻⁶ × 100² = 50 mJ. Energy in 20 μF: U₂ = ½ × 20 × 10⁻⁶ × 100² = 100 mJ. Ratio U₁:U₂ = 50:100 = 1:2. Alternatively, since V is the same for both, U ∝ C, so U₁/U₂ = C₁/C₂ = 10/20 = 1/2.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["charge redistribution", "common potential", "energy ratio"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-dielectric-20", "subtopic": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "topic_name": "Combination of Capacitors and Dielectrics", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "150 V and ratio 1:1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "100 V and ratio 2:1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "200 V and ratio 1:2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "100 V and ratio 1:2", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "150 V would be the common potential if both capacitors were equal (10 μF each). With unequal capacitors, V'' = Q/(C₁ + C₂) = 3000/30 = 100 V.", "misconception": "Averaging the voltage instead of using charge conservation"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The common potential of 100 V is correct, but the ratio 2:1 is inverted. Since both have the same voltage, the energy ratio equals the capacitance ratio C₁:C₂ = 1:2.", "misconception": "Inverting the energy ratio"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "200 V is incorrect. By charge conservation, V'' = 3000/30 = 100 V, not 200 V.", "misconception": null}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b12');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The electric potential at a distance r from a point charge q is given by:", "explanation": "The electric potential due to a point charge q at a distance r is V = kq/r = q/(4πε₀r). This is a scalar quantity and can be positive or negative depending on the sign of the charge.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["electric potential", "point charge", "Coulomb constant"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-01", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "V = kq/r", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "V = kq/r²", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "V = kq²/r", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "V = kr/q", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "kq/r² is the expression for electric field magnitude, not electric potential. Potential varies as 1/r, not 1/r².", "misconception": "Confusing electric field with electric potential"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The charge appears to the first power in the potential formula, not squared.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This expression has incorrect dimensional analysis and does not represent any standard electrostatic quantity.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Electric potential is a scalar quantity. What is the SI unit of electric potential?", "explanation": "The SI unit of electric potential is the volt (V). One volt is defined as one joule per coulomb (1 V = 1 J/C). It represents the potential energy per unit charge at a point in the electric field.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["electric potential", "SI unit", "volt"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-02", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Newton per coulomb (N/C)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Volt (V)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Coulomb per metre (C/m)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Joule (J)", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Newton per coulomb (N/C) is the unit of electric field intensity, not electric potential.", "misconception": "Confusing units of electric field and electric potential"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Coulomb per metre is not a standard unit for any common electrostatic quantity.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Joule is the unit of energy. Electric potential is energy per unit charge, so its unit is J/C = V, not just J.", "misconception": "Confusing potential energy with potential"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The work done in moving a charge of 5 μC between two points having a potential difference of 20 V is:", "explanation": "The work done in moving a charge q through a potential difference ΔV is W = qΔV. Here q = 5 μC = 5 × 10⁻⁶ C and ΔV = 20 V. So W = 5 × 10⁻⁶ × 20 = 100 × 10⁻⁶ J = 100 μJ = 1 × 10⁻⁴ J.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["work done", "potential difference", "charge"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-03", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1 × 10⁻³ J", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "4 × 10⁻⁶ J", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1 × 10⁻⁴ J", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "2.5 × 10⁻⁷ J", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "1 × 10⁻³ J would result from using 50 μC instead of 5 μC, which is ten times the given charge.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "4 × 10⁻⁶ J does not follow from multiplying 5 × 10⁻⁶ C by 20 V.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "2.5 × 10⁻⁷ J would result from dividing charge by potential difference instead of multiplying.", "misconception": "Dividing instead of multiplying q and V"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Eight identical point charges q are placed at the eight corners of a cube of side a. The electrostatic potential energy of the system is (k = 1/4πε₀):", "explanation": "A cube has 8 vertices. Total pairs = C(8,2) = 28. There are three types of pairs by distance: 12 edge pairs (distance a), 12 face-diagonal pairs (distance a√2), and 4 body-diagonal pairs (distance a√3). Total PE = kq²[12/a + 12/(a√2) + 4/(a√3)] = (kq²/a)[12 + 12/√2 + 4/√3] = (kq²/a)[12 + 6√2 + 4√3/3].", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["potential energy of system", "cube arrangement", "multiple charge pairs"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-04", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "(kq²/a)(12 + 6√2)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "(kq²/a)(24 + 12√2 + 4√3)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "(kq²/a)(12 + 12√2 + 4√3)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "(kq²/a)(12 + 6√2 + 4√3/3)", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This expression omits the 4 body-diagonal pairs entirely. A cube has edge, face-diagonal, and body-diagonal pairs — all must be included.", "misconception": "Forgetting body-diagonal pairs in a cube"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The coefficients 24 and 12 are twice the actual number of edge and face-diagonal pairs. There are 12 edges and 12 face diagonals, not 24 and 12.", "misconception": "Double-counting pairs"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The face-diagonal contribution should be 12/(a√2) = 6√2·(kq²/a), not 12√2. Also 4/√3 = 4√3/3, not 4√3.", "misconception": "Error in rationalizing denominators"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Two point charges +4 μC and −4 μC are placed 20 cm apart. The electric potential at the midpoint of the line joining the two charges is:", "explanation": "At the midpoint, the distance from each charge is 10 cm = 0.1 m. Potential due to +4 μC is V₁ = kq/r = 9 × 10⁹ × 4 × 10⁻⁶/0.1 = +3.6 × 10⁵ V. Potential due to −4 μC is V₂ = 9 × 10⁹ × (−4 × 10⁻⁶)/0.1 = −3.6 × 10⁵ V. Total V = V₁ + V₂ = 0.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["superposition of potential", "point charges", "midpoint"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-05", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "3.6 × 10⁵ V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "7.2 × 10⁵ V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "−3.6 × 10⁵ V", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "3.6 × 10⁵ V is the potential due to only the positive charge. You must add the contribution from both charges.", "misconception": "Ignoring the contribution of the negative charge"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "7.2 × 10⁵ V would result from adding the magnitudes without considering the sign of the charges.", "misconception": "Treating potential as always positive like electric field magnitude"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "−3.6 × 10⁵ V is the potential due to only the negative charge; the positive charge contribution must also be included.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The electric potential at a point on the axial line of a short electric dipole at distance r from the centre is proportional to:", "explanation": "The potential due to a short electric dipole at a point on its axial line is V = kp cos θ/r², where θ = 0° for the axial line. Thus V = kp/r², which means V is proportional to 1/r². The potential falls off faster for a dipole compared to a point charge.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["electric dipole", "axial potential", "inverse square"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-06", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1/r", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1/r²", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "1/r³", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1/r⁴", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "1/r dependence is characteristic of the potential due to a point charge, not a dipole.", "misconception": "Confusing point charge potential with dipole potential"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1/r³ dependence is characteristic of the electric field of a dipole, not the potential.", "misconception": "Confusing dipole electric field variation with dipole potential variation"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "No standard electrostatic quantity for a dipole varies as 1/r⁴ in the far-field approximation.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The electric potential at a point on the equatorial plane of a short electric dipole is:", "explanation": "On the equatorial plane of a dipole, the angle θ = 90°. The potential is V = kp cos θ/r² = kp cos 90°/r² = 0. The contributions from the positive and negative charges exactly cancel at every point on the equatorial plane.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["electric dipole", "equatorial potential", "zero potential"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-07", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Positive", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Negative", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Depends on the dipole moment", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Both charges are equidistant from any point on the equatorial plane, so the positive and negative potentials cancel exactly.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The negative charge does not dominate since it is at the same distance as the positive charge from any equatorial point.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "While the individual potentials depend on dipole moment, their sum on the equatorial plane is always zero regardless of the dipole moment magnitude.", "misconception": "Thinking the result depends on dipole moment magnitude"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The relation between electric field E and electric potential V is given by E = −dV/dr. If V = 4x² volt (where x is in metres), the electric field at x = 1 m is:", "explanation": "Given V = 4x², the electric field component along x is E = −dV/dx = −d(4x²)/dx = −8x. At x = 1 m, E = −8(1) = −8 V/m. The magnitude is 8 V/m directed in the negative x-direction.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["relation between E and V", "potential gradient", "differentiation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-08", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4 V/m in negative x-direction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "4 V/m in positive x-direction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "8 V/m in positive x-direction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "8 V/m in negative x-direction", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "4 V/m would result from forgetting to apply the power rule correctly during differentiation of 4x².", "misconception": "Incorrect differentiation of polynomial"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The direction is wrong. E = −dV/dx gives a negative sign, indicating the field points in the negative x-direction.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "While the magnitude 8 V/m is correct, the direction should be negative x since E = −dV/dx and dV/dx is positive.", "misconception": "Forgetting the negative sign in E = −dV/dr"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Three charges of +q, +q, and +q are placed at the three vertices of an equilateral triangle of side a. The electric potential at the centroid of the triangle is:", "explanation": "The distance from each vertex to the centroid of an equilateral triangle with side a is r = a/√3. Since potential is a scalar, the total potential at the centroid is V = 3 × kq/(a/√3) = 3√3 kq/a.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["superposition of potential", "equilateral triangle", "centroid"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-09", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "3kq/a", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "3√3 kq/a", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "√3 kq/a", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "9kq/a", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "3kq/a would be correct only if the distance from vertex to centroid were a, but it is actually a/√3.", "misconception": "Using side length instead of centroid distance"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "√3 kq/a accounts for only one charge contribution with the correct distance, not all three.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "9kq/a is too large and does not follow from the correct distance formula for the centroid.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The electrostatic potential energy of a system of two point charges q₁ = +2 μC and q₂ = −3 μC separated by a distance of 30 cm is:", "explanation": "The potential energy of two point charges is U = kq₁q₂/r. Here U = 9 × 10⁹ × (2 × 10⁻⁶) × (−3 × 10⁻⁶)/0.3 = 9 × 10⁹ × (−6 × 10⁻¹²)/0.3 = −54 × 10⁻³/0.3 = −0.18 J.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["potential energy", "two charge system", "negative energy"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-10", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "+0.18 J", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "−0.06 J", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "−0.18 J", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "+0.06 J", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "+0.18 J has the correct magnitude but wrong sign. Since the charges are opposite, the potential energy must be negative.", "misconception": "Ignoring the sign of charges in potential energy calculation"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "−0.06 J would result from using r = 0.9 m or an incorrect charge product.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "+0.06 J is both the wrong magnitude and wrong sign for this charge configuration.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "The electric potential V in a region varies with distance x as V = 6x² − 4x + 3 (in volts, x in metres). The electric field at x = 2 m in V/m is:", "explanation": "The electric field is E = −dV/dx = −d(6x² − 4x + 3)/dx = −(12x − 4). At x = 2 m, E = −(12 × 2 − 4) = −(24 − 4) = −20 V/m. The magnitude is 20 V/m directed in the negative x-direction.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["potential gradient", "electric field", "differentiation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-11", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "−12 V/m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "+20 V/m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "+12 V/m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "−20 V/m", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "−12 V/m would result from differentiating only the first term (6x²) and ignoring the −4x term.", "misconception": "Incomplete differentiation"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "+20 V/m has the correct magnitude but wrong sign. Remember E = −dV/dx, so the negative sign is essential.", "misconception": "Forgetting the negative sign in E = −dV/dx"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "+12 V/m results from both incomplete differentiation and a sign error.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Four charges +q, +q, −q, and −q are placed at the four corners of a square of side a, with like charges on opposite corners. The total electrostatic potential energy of the system is:", "explanation": "There are 6 pairs in a 4-charge system. The side pairs: 4 pairs of unlike charges at distance a give 4 × k(+q)(−q)/a = −4kq²/a. The diagonal pairs: 2 pairs of like charges at distance a√2 give kq²/(a√2) + kq²/(a√2) = 2kq²/(a√2) = √2 kq²/a. Total U = −4kq²/a + √2 kq²/a = kq²/a(√2 − 4).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["potential energy of system", "multiple charges", "square arrangement"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-12", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "(kq²/a)(√2 − 4)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "(kq²/a)(4 − √2)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "−4kq²/a", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "(kq²/a)(2√2 − 4)", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "(4 − √2) has the wrong sign. The adjacent unlike-charge pairs contribute negative energy that dominates over the diagonal like-charge pairs.", "misconception": "Sign error in summing pair-wise potential energies"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "−4kq²/a accounts for only the 4 side pairs and neglects the 2 diagonal pairs entirely.", "misconception": "Forgetting diagonal pairs in the energy calculation"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "2√2 − 4 would arise from incorrectly counting the diagonal pairs or using wrong distances.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): The electric field is always perpendicular to the equipotential surface at every point.\nReason (R): No work is done in moving a charge along an equipotential surface.", "explanation": "Both the assertion and the reason are correct. If the electric field had a component along the equipotential surface, work would be done in moving a charge along the surface, contradicting the definition of an equipotential surface. Hence R correctly explains A — the perpendicularity ensures zero work along the surface.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["equipotential surface", "electric field direction", "work done"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-13", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "R directly explains why E must be perpendicular — if E had a tangential component, work would be done along the surface, violating the equipotential condition.", "misconception": "Not recognizing the causal link between zero work and perpendicularity"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "R is indeed correct; by definition, no work is done in moving a charge on an equipotential surface since ΔV = 0.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A is a well-established fact in electrostatics — the electric field lines are always normal to equipotential surfaces.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): The electrostatic potential energy of two like charges is positive.\nReason (R): Electric potential is always positive in the region surrounding a positive charge.", "explanation": "The assertion is correct: for two like charges (both positive or both negative), U = kq₁q₂/r is positive since the product q₁q₂ is positive. The reason is also correct: the potential around a positive charge is indeed positive (V = kq/r > 0 when q > 0). However, R does not explain A because A applies to both like positive and like negative charges, and the positivity of PE comes from the product of charges, not from the potential of a single charge.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["potential energy sign", "like charges", "electric potential sign"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-14", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "While both statements are independently true, R does not explain A. Two negative charges also have positive PE, but R talks about potential near positive charges only.", "misconception": "Assuming any two correct statements must be causally related"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "R is a correct statement — the potential around a positive point charge is indeed positive at all points.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A is correct — like charges (++ or −−) always give a positive product q₁q₂, making U = kq₁q₂/r positive.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the following physical situations (Column I) with the corresponding electric potential (Column II):\n\nColumn I:\nA. Inside a uniformly charged spherical shell\nB. At the surface of a uniformly charged spherical shell of radius R\nC. At a distance 2R from the centre of a uniformly charged spherical shell\nD. At infinity\n\nColumn II:\n1. Zero\n2. kQ/R\n3. kQ/2R\n4. kQ/R (same as at surface)", "explanation": "Inside the shell (A), the potential is constant and equal to the surface potential: kQ/R, so A→4. At the surface (B), V = kQ/R, so B→2. At distance 2R (C), V = kQ/2R, so C→3. At infinity (D), V = 0, so D→1.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["spherical shell potential", "potential variation", "matching"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-15", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-3, B-2, C-4, D-1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A-1 implies zero potential inside the shell, which is incorrect. The potential inside is constant and equal to the surface potential kQ/R.", "misconception": "Confusing zero electric field inside shell with zero potential"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "A-2 and B-4 both give kQ/R but the match labels are swapped incorrectly in the list structure.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A-3 would give kQ/2R inside the shell, which is wrong. The potential inside is kQ/R, not kQ/2R.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the following quantities (Column I) with their distance dependence from a point charge (Column II):\n\nColumn I:\nA. Electric field due to point charge\nB. Electric potential due to point charge\nC. Electric field due to dipole (far field)\nD. Electric potential due to dipole (far field)\n\nColumn II:\n1. ∝ 1/r\n2. ∝ 1/r²\n3. ∝ 1/r³\n4. ∝ 1/r⁴", "explanation": "Electric field due to a point charge E = kq/r², so A→2. Electric potential due to a point charge V = kq/r, so B→1. Electric field due to a dipole varies as 1/r³, so C→3. Electric potential due to a dipole varies as 1/r², so D→2. Hence the correct matching is A-2, B-1, C-3, D-2.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["distance dependence", "point charge", "dipole", "field and potential"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-16", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-3, D-2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A-1 would mean E ∝ 1/r for a point charge, but the correct dependence is E ∝ 1/r² (Coulomb''s law).", "misconception": "Confusing potential and field dependence for point charge"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "C-4 would mean dipole field varies as 1/r⁴, which is incorrect. Dipole field varies as 1/r³.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A-1 and B-2 are swapped — field goes as 1/r² and potential goes as 1/r for a point charge.", "misconception": "Mixing up field and potential dependencies"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Equipotential surfaces due to a point charge are concentric spheres centred on the charge.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. For a point charge, the potential V = kq/r depends only on the distance r from the charge. All points at the same distance r have the same potential, forming concentric spherical surfaces centred on the charge.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["equipotential surface", "point charge", "spherical symmetry"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-17", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The statement is correct. Since V = kq/r, all points at equal distance r from the charge have the same potential, forming concentric spheres.", "misconception": "Thinking equipotential surfaces might have a different geometry for point charges"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Two equipotential surfaces can intersect each other.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. If two equipotential surfaces intersected, the point of intersection would have two different values of potential simultaneously, which is physically impossible since potential is a single-valued function of position.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["equipotential surface", "properties", "intersection"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-18", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "If two equipotential surfaces intersected, the point of intersection would have two different potential values, which violates the definition of a scalar field.", "misconception": "Thinking equipotential surfaces can cross like field lines in some cases"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A charge of 10 μC is placed at the origin. The potential at a point 0.3 m from the charge is _____ V. (Take k = 9 × 10⁹ N m² C⁻²)", "explanation": "Using V = kq/r = 9 × 10⁹ × 10 × 10⁻⁶ / 0.3 = 9 × 10⁹ × 10⁻⁵ / 0.3 = 9 × 10⁴ / 0.3 = 3 × 10⁵ V. The potential is 3 × 10⁵ V or 300000 V.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["electric potential calculation", "point charge", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-19", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "3 × 10⁴", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "9 × 10⁵", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "3 × 10⁶", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "3 × 10⁵", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "3 × 10⁴ is ten times too small. Check the power of ten in the calculation: 9 × 10⁹ × 10⁻⁵ = 9 × 10⁴, and dividing by 0.3 gives 3 × 10⁵.", "misconception": "Error in handling powers of ten"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "9 × 10⁵ would result from not dividing by 0.3 or using an incorrect distance.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "3 × 10⁶ is ten times too large, likely from using the charge as 100 μC instead of 10 μC.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-electrostatics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-es-potential", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a laboratory experiment, a student places a +5 μC charge at point A and a +10 μC charge at point B, separated by a distance of 1 m. She wants to find a point on the line joining A and B where the electric potential is zero. She assumes both charges are in free space.\n\nThe student''s observation should be that:", "explanation": "Since both charges are positive, the potential V = kq₁/r₁ + kq₂/r₂ is always positive at every point on the line joining them (and everywhere in space, since both terms are positive). There is no point where the net potential is zero. For potential to be zero between two charges, the charges must be of opposite sign.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["superposition of potential", "like charges", "zero potential"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-pot-potential-20", "subtopic": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "topic_name": "Electric Potential and Potential Energy", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The zero potential point lies between A and B at 1/3 m from A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "The zero potential point lies between A and B at the midpoint", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "No point on the line joining A and B has zero potential", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "The zero potential point lies outside AB at 1 m from B", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This would be the null point for electric field (not potential) between charges of different magnitudes, and even then only for opposite charges would potential be zero between them.", "misconception": "Confusing zero field point with zero potential point"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "At the midpoint, both positive charges contribute positive potentials, so the net potential is positive, not zero.", "misconception": "Assuming symmetry implies zero potential"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Even outside the charges, both positive charges contribute positive potentials at all points, so the potential cannot be zero anywhere.", "misconception": null}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b12');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "At resonance in a series LCR circuit, the impedance of the circuit is equal to:", "explanation": "At resonance, the inductive reactance (XL) equals the capacitive reactance (XC), so they cancel each other. The impedance Z = √(R² + (XL − XC)²) reduces to Z = R. The circuit behaves as a purely resistive circuit at the resonant frequency.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["resonance", "LCR-circuit", "impedance", "resistance"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-01", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "XL − XC", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "R", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "√(R² + XL²)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "At resonance XL = XC, so XL − XC = 0. This would give zero impedance, which is not correct since resistance R is still present.", "misconception": "Forgetting that R remains even when reactances cancel"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This expression ignores the capacitive reactance. At resonance, XL and XC cancel, leaving only R, not √(R² + XL²).", "misconception": "Using the formula for an RL circuit instead of a resonant LCR circuit"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Zero impedance would mean infinite current, which is physically impossible. The resistance R always contributes to impedance.", "misconception": "Thinking total impedance becomes zero when reactances cancel"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The resonant angular frequency of a series LCR circuit with L = 0.5 H and C = 2 μF is:", "explanation": "The resonant angular frequency is ω₀ = 1/√(LC) = 1/√(0.5 × 2 × 10⁻⁶) = 1/√(10⁻⁶) = 1/10⁻³ = 1000 rad/s. At this frequency, the inductive and capacitive reactances are equal and the circuit draws maximum current.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["resonant-frequency", "inductance", "capacitance", "LCR-circuit"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-02", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "500 rad/s", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "100 rad/s", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1000 rad/s", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "2000 rad/s", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "500 rad/s might result from incorrectly using ω₀ = 1/(2√(LC)) or a calculation error. The correct formula gives 1/√(10⁻⁶) = 10³.", "misconception": "Introducing an extra factor of 2 in the resonance formula"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "100 rad/s is too small. Check the unit conversion: C = 2 μF = 2 × 10⁻⁶ F, and √(0.5 × 2 × 10⁻⁶) = 10⁻³.", "misconception": "Error in converting microfarads to farads"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "2000 rad/s would result from using ω₀ = 2/√(LC) or a similar error. The correct value is 1/√(LC) = 1000 rad/s.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In a step-up transformer, the voltage in the secondary coil compared to the primary coil is:", "explanation": "A step-up transformer increases voltage from primary to secondary. The turns ratio Ns/Np > 1, so by the transformer equation Vs/Vp = Ns/Np, the secondary voltage is greater than the primary voltage. Correspondingly, the secondary current is less than the primary current (for an ideal transformer, VsIs = VpIp).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["step-up-transformer", "voltage", "turns-ratio"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-03", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Higher", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Lower", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Same", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Lower voltage in the secondary would describe a step-down transformer, not a step-up transformer.", "misconception": "Confusing step-up and step-down transformers"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "If the voltages were the same, the turns ratio would be 1:1, which is neither a step-up nor a step-down transformer.", "misconception": "Thinking a transformer always gives the same output voltage"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Zero secondary voltage would mean no energy transfer at all, which defeats the purpose of a transformer.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The quality factor (Q-factor) of a series LCR resonant circuit is given by:", "explanation": "The quality factor Q = ω₀L/R = (1/R)√(L/C). It measures the sharpness of the resonance curve. A higher Q means a sharper peak and a narrower bandwidth. The Q-factor can also be written as Q = 1/(ω₀CR), since ω₀ = 1/√(LC), giving ω₀L = L/√(LC) = √(L/C).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["quality-factor", "resonance", "sharpness", "bandwidth"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-04", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "R/(ω₀L)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "ω₀CR", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "R√(LC)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "ω₀L/R", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "R/(ω₀L) is the reciprocal of the Q-factor. A higher R would increase this expression, but physically a higher R makes resonance less sharp, so Q should decrease with R.", "misconception": "Inverting the Q-factor formula"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "ω₀CR is also the reciprocal of Q. Since Q = 1/(ω₀CR), this expression equals 1/Q, not Q.", "misconception": "Confusing Q with 1/Q"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "R√(LC) has dimensions of time, not a dimensionless quantity. The Q-factor must be dimensionless.", "misconception": "Incorrectly combining variables without dimensional analysis"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The power factor of a series LCR circuit at resonance is:", "explanation": "The power factor cos φ = R/Z. At resonance, XL = XC, so Z = R. Therefore, cos φ = R/R = 1, and the phase angle φ = 0°. This means voltage and current are in phase, and the circuit draws maximum power P = VrmsIrms.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["power-factor", "resonance", "phase-angle", "impedance"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-05", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "0", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.5", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Infinity", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "A power factor of 0 occurs when the circuit is purely reactive (φ = 90°). At resonance, the reactive components cancel, so the power factor cannot be zero.", "misconception": "Confusing resonance condition with purely reactive circuit"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A power factor of 0.5 would mean φ = 60°, which occurs only at specific off-resonance frequencies, not at resonance.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The power factor cos φ is bounded between 0 and 1, so it can never be infinity.", "misconception": "Confusing power factor with Q-factor or impedance"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "An ideal transformer has 200 turns in the primary and 1000 turns in the secondary. If the primary voltage is 220 V, the secondary voltage is:", "explanation": "For an ideal transformer, Vs/Vp = Ns/Np. Therefore Vs = Vp × (Ns/Np) = 220 × (1000/200) = 220 × 5 = 1100 V. Since Ns > Np, this is a step-up transformer that increases voltage by a factor of 5.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["transformer", "turns-ratio", "voltage-transformation", "ideal-transformer"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-06", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "44 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "220 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "550 V", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1100 V", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "44 V = 220/5 would result from using the inverted ratio Np/Ns instead of Ns/Np. Since Ns > Np, the voltage must increase, not decrease.", "misconception": "Using the inverse turns ratio for voltage"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "220 V would mean no voltage change, implying a 1:1 turns ratio. But Ns/Np = 1000/200 = 5, so voltage must change.", "misconception": "Ignoring the turns ratio entirely"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "550 V = 220 × 2.5 would result from using Ns/Np = 1000/400 or another calculation error. The correct ratio is 1000/200 = 5.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in the turns ratio calculation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a purely inductive AC circuit, the wattless component of current is:", "explanation": "In a purely inductive circuit, the phase angle φ = 90° (current lags voltage by π/2). The wattless (reactive) component of current = I sin φ = I sin 90° = I. Since all the current is wattless, no power is dissipated. The power consumed P = VrmsIrms cos 90° = 0.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["wattless-current", "purely-inductive", "phase-angle", "reactive-component"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-07", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Equal to the total current I", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "I/√2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "I/2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Zero wattless current would mean all current is power-producing (φ = 0°), which describes a purely resistive circuit, not a purely inductive one.", "misconception": "Confusing wattless component with the power-producing component"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "I/√2 as the wattless component would imply φ = 45°, which is not the case for a purely inductive circuit where φ = 90°.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "I/2 as the wattless component would imply sin φ = 0.5, i.e., φ = 30°. In a purely inductive circuit, φ = 90° and sin φ = 1.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Electrical power is transmitted over long distances at high voltage because:", "explanation": "Power loss in transmission lines is P_loss = I²R. For a given power P = VI, increasing voltage V allows a proportional decrease in current I (since I = P/V). Since power loss depends on I², doubling voltage reduces current by half and losses by a factor of 4. Hence, high-voltage transmission minimises resistive losses.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["power-transmission", "high-voltage", "power-loss", "current-reduction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-08", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "It increases the total power delivered", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "It reduces the resistance of the transmission line", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "It reduces the current, thereby reducing I²R losses", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "It makes the power factor of the line equal to 1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The total power generated at the source remains the same; only the fraction lost in transmission decreases. High voltage does not create more power.", "misconception": "Thinking high voltage creates additional power"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Resistance depends on the wire material, length, and cross-section. Increasing voltage does not change the physical resistance of the line.", "misconception": "Confusing the effect of voltage on current with a change in resistance"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Power factor depends on the load characteristics, not on the transmission voltage. High voltage transmission does not automatically correct power factor.", "misconception": "Confusing voltage level with power factor correction"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A series LCR circuit has L = 10 mH, C = 10 μF, and R = 10 Ω. The quality factor (Q) of the circuit is:", "explanation": "First find ω₀ = 1/√(LC) = 1/√(10 × 10⁻³ × 10 × 10⁻⁶) = 1/√(10⁻⁷) = 1/(10⁻³·⁵) = √10 × 10³ ≈ 3162 rad/s. Alternatively, Q = (1/R)√(L/C) = (1/10)√(10 × 10⁻³/(10 × 10⁻⁶)) = (1/10)√(10³) = (1/10) × 31.62 ≈ 3.16. Rounding, Q ≈ √10 ≈ 3.16.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["quality-factor", "LCR-circuit", "resonance", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-09", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "10", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "√10 ≈ 3.16", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "100", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Q = 1 would require √(L/C) = R = 10, i.e., L/C = 100. But L/C = 10⁻² / 10⁻⁵ = 10³, so √(L/C) = √1000 ≈ 31.6, and Q = 31.6/10 ≈ 3.16.", "misconception": "Errors in unit conversion of L and C"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Q = 10 would require √(L/C)/R = 10, i.e., √(L/C) = 100. But √(L/C) = √(10³) ≈ 31.6.", "misconception": "Incorrectly computing the ratio L/C"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Q = 100 is far too large for these values. With R = 10 Ω, Q = ω₀L/R = 3162 × 0.01/10 ≈ 3.16.", "misconception": "Forgetting to convert millihenry and microfarad to SI units"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "An ideal transformer steps down voltage from 2200 V to 220 V. If the secondary coil has 50 turns, and the power delivered to a load of 44 Ω connected across the secondary is:", "explanation": "Secondary voltage Vs = 220 V. The current in the secondary Is = Vs/R_load = 220/44 = 5 A. Power delivered to the load P = Vs × Is = 220 × 5 = 1100 W. Alternatively, P = Vs²/R_load = (220)²/44 = 48400/44 = 1100 W. For the ideal transformer, this equals the power drawn from the primary.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["ideal-transformer", "power", "step-down", "load-resistance"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-10", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "550 W", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1100 W", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "2200 W", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "110 W", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "550 W might result from using P = Vs²/(2R) or halving the correct answer. The correct formula is P = Vs²/R = (220)²/44 = 1100 W.", "misconception": "Introducing an unnecessary factor of 2 in the power formula"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "2200 W could result from using the primary voltage (2200 V) with the secondary load resistance, which is incorrect since the load is connected across the secondary.", "misconception": "Using primary voltage with secondary load resistance"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "110 W = 220²/440, which uses an incorrect load resistance. The given load is 44 Ω, not 440 Ω.", "misconception": "Decimal error in the load resistance"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In a series LCR circuit, L = 0.1 H, C = 10 μF, and R = 5 Ω. The bandwidth (Δω) of the resonant circuit is:", "explanation": "The bandwidth of a series LCR resonant circuit is Δω = R/L. Substituting values: Δω = 5/0.1 = 50 rad/s. The bandwidth is independent of capacitance and depends only on R and L. A smaller bandwidth (larger Q) indicates a sharper resonance peak. Here Q = ω₀L/R = (1/√(LC)) × L/R = (1000 × 0.1)/5 = 20, and Δω = ω₀/Q = 1000/20 = 50 rad/s, confirming the result.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["bandwidth", "resonance", "sharpness", "LCR-circuit"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-11", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "50 rad/s", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "500 rad/s", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "100 rad/s", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1000 rad/s", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "500 rad/s might result from using Δω = R/L with L in mH instead of H. Ensure L = 0.1 H, then Δω = 5/0.1 = 50 rad/s.", "misconception": "Unit conversion error with inductance"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "100 rad/s could come from incorrectly using Δω = 2R/L. The correct formula is Δω = R/L = 50 rad/s.", "misconception": "Introducing a spurious factor of 2 in the bandwidth formula"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "1000 rad/s is the resonant frequency ω₀ = 1/√(LC), not the bandwidth. Bandwidth Δω = R/L = 50 rad/s is much smaller than ω₀.", "misconception": "Confusing resonant frequency with bandwidth"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A power station delivers 500 kW of power at 10,000 V to a distant town through cables of total resistance 20 Ω. If the voltage is stepped up to 100,000 V before transmission, the ratio of power loss at 100,000 V to power loss at 10,000 V is:", "explanation": "At 10,000 V: I₁ = P/V₁ = 500 × 10³/10⁴ = 50 A, so P_loss₁ = I₁²R = 50² × 20 = 50,000 W. At 100,000 V: I₂ = P/V₂ = 500 × 10³/10⁵ = 5 A, so P_loss₂ = I₂²R = 5² × 20 = 500 W. Ratio = P_loss₂/P_loss₁ = 500/50,000 = 1/100. Stepping up voltage by 10 times reduces losses by 10² = 100 times.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["power-loss", "transmission", "high-voltage", "current-reduction", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-12", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1 : 10", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1 : 1000", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1 : 10,000", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1 : 100", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "1:10 would be correct if power loss were proportional to I (first power), but P_loss = I²R, so the ratio goes as the square of the voltage ratio.", "misconception": "Using P_loss ∝ I instead of P_loss ∝ I²"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "1:1000 would result from cubing the voltage ratio (10³). Since P_loss ∝ 1/V², the ratio is (V₁/V₂)² = (10)² = 100.", "misconception": "Using an incorrect power law for the voltage dependence"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1:10,000 = 1/10⁴ corresponds to the fourth power of the voltage ratio, which is not the correct relationship. The correct law gives 1/10² = 1/100.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): At resonance in a series LCR circuit, the current in the circuit is maximum.\nReason (R): At resonance, the impedance of the circuit is minimum and equals the resistance R.", "explanation": "Both A and R are correct, and R correctly explains A. At resonance, XL = XC, so the impedance Z = √(R² + (XL − XC)²) = R, which is the minimum possible value of impedance. Since I = V/Z, the minimum impedance leads to maximum current. Thus the reason directly explains the assertion.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["resonance", "maximum-current", "minimum-impedance", "LCR-circuit"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-13", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The fact that impedance is minimum (Z = R) is exactly why current is maximum (I = V/Z). The reason is the direct cause of the assertion.", "misconception": "Failing to see the direct causal link between minimum impedance and maximum current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is correct: at resonance XL = XC, so Z = √(R² + 0) = R, which is indeed the minimum impedance.", "misconception": "Thinking impedance does not reduce to R at resonance"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct: since Z is minimum at resonance, I = V/Z is indeed maximum at that frequency.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): A transformer cannot work with direct current (DC).\nReason (R): A transformer operates on the principle of mutual induction, which requires a changing magnetic flux.", "explanation": "Both A and R are correct, and R is the correct explanation of A. A transformer works on Faraday''s law of electromagnetic induction: an EMF is induced in the secondary only when the magnetic flux through it changes. DC produces a steady current and hence a constant magnetic flux, which cannot induce any EMF in the secondary coil. Therefore, transformers inherently require alternating current.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["transformer", "mutual-induction", "DC", "changing-flux", "Faraday-law"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-14", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The requirement for changing flux (R) is precisely the reason DC cannot work in a transformer (A). Steady DC means no flux change, no induced EMF, so R directly explains A.", "misconception": "Not recognising that mutual induction requires time-varying flux as the root cause"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is factually correct: mutual induction does require a changing magnetic flux according to Faraday''s law.", "misconception": "Thinking a constant flux can still induce EMF"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct: connecting DC to a transformer primary produces constant flux, yielding zero secondary EMF (except transiently at switch-on).", "misconception": "Believing a transformer can operate continuously on DC"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the following AC circuit parameters (Column-I) with their expressions (Column-II):\n\nColumn-I:\nA. Resonant frequency\nB. Power factor\nC. Quality factor\nD. Impedance at resonance\n\nColumn-II:\n1. R/Z\n2. 1/√(LC)\n3. ω₀L/R\n4. R", "explanation": "Resonant angular frequency ω₀ = 1/√(LC), so A→2. Power factor cos φ = R/Z, so B→1. Quality factor Q = ω₀L/R, so C→3. At resonance, impedance Z = R, so D→4. Each expression follows from the standard series LCR circuit analysis.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["resonant-frequency", "power-factor", "quality-factor", "impedance", "matching"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-15", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-2, B-3, C-1, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-4, B-1, C-3, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-3, B-2, C-4, D-1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This assigns R/Z to the Q-factor and ω₀L/R to power factor. Power factor is cos φ = R/Z (B→1), not ω₀L/R. The Q-factor is ω₀L/R (C→3).", "misconception": "Swapping the expressions for power factor and quality factor"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This assigns R to resonant frequency and 1/√(LC) to impedance at resonance. Resonant frequency is 1/√(LC), and impedance at resonance is R.", "misconception": "Swapping resonant frequency and impedance at resonance"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This completely scrambles the matching. Resonant frequency is 1/√(LC) (→2), not ω₀L/R (→3).", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the following types of energy losses in a transformer (Column-I) with their descriptions/remedies (Column-II):\n\nColumn-I:\nA. Copper loss\nB. Eddy current loss\nC. Hysteresis loss\nD. Flux leakage\n\nColumn-II:\n1. Reduced by using a laminated core\n2. Reduced by using soft iron core with narrow hysteresis loop\n3. Caused by I²R heating of the windings\n4. Reduced by winding coils over one another", "explanation": "Copper loss is due to I²R heating in the windings (A→3). Eddy current loss is reduced by using a laminated core that interrupts eddy current paths (B→1). Hysteresis loss is reduced by using a soft iron core with a narrow hysteresis loop (C→2). Flux leakage is reduced by winding the primary and secondary coils over one another to maximise coupling (D→4).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["transformer-losses", "copper-loss", "eddy-currents", "hysteresis", "flux-leakage"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-16", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-3, B-2, C-1, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-3, B-1, C-2, D-4", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-1, B-3, C-4, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-4, B-1, C-2, D-3", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps eddy current loss and hysteresis loss remedies. Lamination (1) reduces eddy currents (B), and soft iron with narrow hysteresis loop (2) reduces hysteresis loss (C).", "misconception": "Confusing the remedies for eddy current and hysteresis losses"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This assigns lamination to copper loss and I²R heating to eddy currents. Copper loss is due to I²R in windings (→3), and lamination reduces eddy currents (→1).", "misconception": "Mixing up the causes and remedies of different transformer losses"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This assigns winding over one another to copper loss and I²R heating to flux leakage. Winding coils together reduces flux leakage (D→4), and I²R heating is copper loss (A→3).", "misconception": "Reversing copper loss and flux leakage descriptions"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In an ideal transformer, the input power is equal to the output power.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. An ideal transformer has no energy losses (no copper loss, no iron loss, no flux leakage). By conservation of energy, the power input to the primary coil equals the power output from the secondary coil: VpIp = VsIs. This is the fundamental assumption of an ideal transformer.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["ideal-transformer", "power-conservation", "input-output-power"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-17", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "In an ideal transformer, there are no energy losses. Conservation of energy demands that input power equals output power: VpIp = VsIs.", "misconception": "Thinking that voltage transformation implies power transformation, or confusing real transformers with ideal ones"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The power factor of a purely capacitive AC circuit is 1.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. In a purely capacitive circuit, the current leads the voltage by 90° (φ = 90°). The power factor cos φ = cos 90° = 0, not 1. A power factor of 1 occurs only in a purely resistive circuit or at resonance in a series LCR circuit. In a purely capacitive circuit, no real power is dissipated.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["power-factor", "purely-capacitive", "phase-angle", "wattless-current"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-18", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A purely capacitive circuit has a phase angle of 90° between voltage and current. Power factor = cos 90° = 0, not 1. Only a purely resistive circuit has power factor 1.", "misconception": "Confusing purely capacitive circuit behaviour with purely resistive circuit behaviour"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In an LC oscillating circuit with inductance L = 0.5 H and capacitance C = 8 μF, the angular frequency of oscillation is _____ rad/s.", "explanation": "The angular frequency of LC oscillations is ω = 1/√(LC) = 1/√(0.5 × 8 × 10⁻⁶) = 1/√(4 × 10⁻⁶) = 1/(2 × 10⁻³) = 500 rad/s. This is the natural frequency at which the energy oscillates between the inductor (magnetic energy) and capacitor (electric energy).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["LC-oscillation", "angular-frequency", "inductance", "capacitance", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-19", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "250", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1000", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "50", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "500", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "250 rad/s would result from using ω = 1/(2√(LC)) instead of the correct ω = 1/√(LC). There is no factor of 2 in the angular frequency formula.", "misconception": "Confusing angular frequency ω with frequency f (ω = 2πf, but ω = 1/√(LC), not 1/(2√(LC)))"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "1000 rad/s could result from a unit conversion error, such as using C = 4 μF instead of 8 μF. Double-check: LC = 0.5 × 8 × 10⁻⁶ = 4 × 10⁻⁶.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in computing LC product"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "50 rad/s is too small by a factor of 10. Verify: 1/√(4 × 10⁻⁶) = 1/(2 × 10⁻³) = 500, not 50.", "misconception": "Error in evaluating the square root of 10⁻⁶"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-induction", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-em-transformer", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A small town receives electrical power from a power plant 10 km away. The power plant generates 100 kW at 500 V. The two-wire transmission line has a total resistance of 4 Ω. An engineer proposes using a step-up transformer at the plant to raise the voltage to 5000 V before transmission and a step-down transformer at the town to bring it back to 500 V.\n\nWhat is the power loss in the transmission line WITHOUT the transformer?", "explanation": "Without the transformer, V = 500 V and P = 100 kW = 100,000 W. The current in the transmission line I = P/V = 100,000/500 = 200 A. Power loss P_loss = I²R = (200)² × 4 = 40,000 × 4 = 160,000 W = 160 kW. This is more than the generated power, meaning essentially all power (and more from the source trying to maintain 100 kW delivery) would be lost. With the transformer at 5000 V: I = 100,000/5000 = 20 A, P_loss = (20)² × 4 = 1600 W = 1.6 kW, a massive reduction.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["power-transmission", "power-loss", "transformer", "high-voltage", "scenario", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-ac-transformer-20", "subtopic": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "topic_name": "Resonance, Power Factor, and Transformers", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "40 kW", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "80 kW", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "160 kW", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "1.6 kW", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "40 kW corresponds to I²R with I = 100 A, which would mean P/V = 100,000/1000. The actual current at 500 V is I = 100,000/500 = 200 A.", "misconception": "Using an incorrect voltage to calculate the transmission current"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "80 kW = (200)² × 2 would result from using only half the total line resistance (one wire instead of both). The total two-wire resistance is 4 Ω.", "misconception": "Using only one-way resistance instead of total line resistance"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "1.6 kW is the power loss AFTER stepping up to 5000 V (I = 20 A, P_loss = 400 × 4 = 1600 W). The question asks for loss WITHOUT the transformer.", "misconception": "Calculating the loss with the transformer instead of without it"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b12');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Electromagnetic waves are produced by:", "explanation": "Electromagnetic waves are produced by accelerating (or oscillating) charges. A charge at rest produces only an electrostatic field, and a charge in uniform motion produces both electric and magnetic fields but no radiation. Only when a charge accelerates does it radiate energy in the form of electromagnetic waves, as described by Maxwell''s theory.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["em-wave-production", "accelerating-charge", "maxwell-theory"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-01", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A stationary charge", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A charge moving with constant velocity", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A static magnetic field", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "An accelerating charge", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A stationary charge produces only a static electric field (Coulomb field). It does not radiate electromagnetic waves.", "misconception": "Thinking any charge produces EM waves"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "A charge moving with constant velocity produces a steady magnetic field in addition to its electric field, but does not radiate EM waves. Radiation requires acceleration.", "misconception": "Confusing steady current''s magnetic field with EM radiation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A static magnetic field stores energy but does not propagate as an electromagnetic wave. Time-varying fields are needed for wave propagation.", "misconception": "Confusing static fields with electromagnetic radiation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In an electromagnetic wave, the electric field vector E and the magnetic field vector B are:", "explanation": "Electromagnetic waves are transverse waves in which the electric field E and the magnetic field B oscillate perpendicular to each other and both are perpendicular to the direction of propagation. If the wave travels along the z-axis, E might oscillate along the x-axis and B along the y-axis. This mutual perpendicularity is a fundamental property of EM waves.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["transverse-wave", "E-perpendicular-B", "wave-propagation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-02", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Parallel to each other and parallel to the direction of propagation", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Perpendicular to each other and perpendicular to the direction of propagation", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Parallel to each other but perpendicular to the direction of propagation", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Perpendicular to each other but parallel to the direction of propagation", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "If E and B were parallel to the direction of propagation, the wave would be longitudinal, not transverse. EM waves are strictly transverse.", "misconception": "Confusing EM waves with longitudinal waves like sound"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "E and B are never parallel to each other in a plane EM wave. They are always mutually perpendicular, forming a right-handed coordinate system with the propagation direction.", "misconception": "Thinking E and B oscillate in the same plane"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Neither E nor B is parallel to the direction of propagation. Both oscillate perpendicular to the propagation direction, making EM waves transverse.", "misconception": "Thinking one of the field vectors points along the direction of travel"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The speed of electromagnetic waves in vacuum is given by:", "explanation": "Maxwell showed that the speed of electromagnetic waves in vacuum is c = 1/√(μ₀ε₀), where μ₀ is the permeability of free space and ε₀ is the permittivity of free space. Substituting the known values of μ₀ and ε₀ yields c ≈ 3 × 10⁸ m/s, which matches the experimentally measured speed of light, confirming that light is an electromagnetic wave.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["speed-of-light", "mu-epsilon", "maxwell-relation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-03", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "c = 1/√(μ₀ε₀)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "c = √(μ₀ε₀)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "c = μ₀ε₀", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "c = 1/(μ₀ε₀)", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "√(μ₀ε₀) has dimensions of s/m (inverse of speed). The correct expression is the reciprocal: 1/√(μ₀ε₀), which has dimensions of m/s.", "misconception": "Inverting the formula for the speed of light"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "μ₀ε₀ has dimensions of 1/c² (s²/m²), not m/s. The speed of light involves the square root and reciprocal of this product.", "misconception": "Not applying the square root in Maxwell''s velocity relation"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "1/(μ₀ε₀) has dimensions of m²/s², which is the square of speed (c²), not c itself. The correct formula has a square root.", "misconception": "Forgetting to take the square root, giving c² instead of c"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Maxwell''s displacement current arises due to:", "explanation": "Maxwell introduced the concept of displacement current to account for the continuity of current in circuits containing capacitors. The displacement current is not a flow of actual charges but is proportional to the rate of change of electric flux (dΦE/dt) between the capacitor plates. It is given by Id = ε₀(dΦE/dt). This term was added to Ampere''s law to make it consistent with the continuity equation and led to the prediction of electromagnetic waves.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["displacement-current", "changing-electric-flux", "maxwell-correction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-04", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Flow of electrons between capacitor plates", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A changing magnetic flux", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A time-varying electric field (changing electric flux)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A steady electric field between the plates", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "No actual electrons flow across the gap between capacitor plates (the dielectric or vacuum prevents this). The displacement current exists even in vacuum — it is due to the changing electric field, not charge flow.", "misconception": "Thinking displacement current involves actual charge transport"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "A changing magnetic flux produces an induced EMF (Faraday''s law), not displacement current. Displacement current specifically involves a time-varying electric field.", "misconception": "Confusing Faraday''s law with Maxwell''s displacement current concept"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A steady (constant) electric field has dE/dt = 0, which means zero displacement current. The field must be changing with time to produce displacement current.", "misconception": "Not recognizing that displacement current requires a time-varying field"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A parallel plate capacitor with plate area A and plate separation d is being charged by a constant current I. The displacement current in the region between the plates is:", "explanation": "The displacement current Id = ε₀(dΦE/dt). The electric field between the plates is E = Q/(ε₀A), so the electric flux ΦE = EA = Q/ε₀. Therefore, dΦE/dt = (1/ε₀)(dQ/dt) = I/ε₀. Thus Id = ε₀ × (I/ε₀) = I. The displacement current between the plates is exactly equal to the conduction current I in the connecting wires, ensuring continuity of current in the circuit.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["displacement-current", "capacitor-charging", "current-continuity"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-05", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "I × (d/A)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "ε₀ × I × A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "I (equal to the conduction current)", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "If displacement current were zero between the plates, Ampere''s circuital law would give different results depending on the chosen surface. Maxwell showed that displacement current bridges this gap.", "misconception": "Thinking no current exists between the capacitor plates"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The displacement current does not depend on the plate separation d. It equals the conduction current regardless of plate geometry, ensuring current continuity.", "misconception": "Incorrectly introducing geometric factors into the displacement current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "ε₀ × I × A has incorrect dimensions (A·m²·s⁴/kg·m³ = not ampere). The displacement current must have units of ampere, and it simply equals I.", "misconception": "Incorrectly multiplying by ε₀ and area"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Which of the following electromagnetic waves has the highest frequency?", "explanation": "The electromagnetic spectrum in order of increasing frequency is: radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet, X-rays, gamma rays. Gamma rays have the highest frequency (and shortest wavelength) in the electromagnetic spectrum, typically with frequencies above 3 × 10¹⁹ Hz. They are produced by nuclear reactions and radioactive decay.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["em-spectrum", "frequency-order", "gamma-rays"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-06", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Gamma rays", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "X-rays", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Ultraviolet rays", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Microwaves", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "X-rays have very high frequency but gamma rays have even higher frequency. Gamma rays sit at the extreme high-frequency end of the EM spectrum.", "misconception": "Placing X-rays at the highest frequency end of the spectrum"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Ultraviolet rays have higher frequency than visible light but lower frequency than X-rays and gamma rays.", "misconception": "Not knowing the complete ordering of the EM spectrum"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Microwaves have relatively low frequency, between radio waves and infrared. They are far below gamma rays in frequency.", "misconception": "Confusing the position of microwaves in the EM spectrum"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The ratio of the amplitudes of the electric and magnetic fields (E₀/B₀) in an electromagnetic wave travelling in vacuum is equal to:", "explanation": "In an electromagnetic wave in vacuum, the electric and magnetic field amplitudes are related by E₀/B₀ = c = 3 × 10⁸ m/s. This follows from Maxwell''s equations and means that E₀ is much larger in magnitude than B₀ in SI units. At any instant, E = cB for the wave fields. The ratio has dimensions of velocity.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["E-B-ratio", "speed-of-light", "em-wave-properties"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-07", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "c (speed of light in vacuum)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "1/c", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "c²", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "E₀ and B₀ have different units (V/m and T respectively), so their ratio cannot be a dimensionless number like 1. The ratio E₀/B₀ has dimensions of m/s.", "misconception": "Assuming E and B have equal magnitudes in all unit systems"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1/c = B₀/E₀, which is the reciprocal of the correct ratio. If you write B₀ = E₀/c, then E₀/B₀ = c, not 1/c.", "misconception": "Inverting the E-B amplitude relationship"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "c² has dimensions of m²/s², whereas E₀/B₀ has dimensions of m/s. The ratio is c, not c².", "misconception": "Confusing the E/B ratio with the expression for c² = 1/(μ₀ε₀)"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Which of the following electromagnetic radiations is used in RADAR systems?", "explanation": "RADAR (Radio Detection and Ranging) systems use microwaves because of their short wavelength (compared to radio waves) which allows them to detect smaller objects and provide better angular resolution. Microwaves can penetrate fog, rain, and clouds to some extent, making them ideal for detecting aircraft and ships. Typical RADAR frequencies range from about 1 GHz to 300 GHz.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["microwaves", "radar", "em-wave-applications"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-08", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Infrared radiation", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Ultraviolet radiation", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Microwaves", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Gamma rays", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Infrared radiation is primarily used for thermal imaging, remote controls, and night vision. It is not used in RADAR systems.", "misconception": "Confusing infrared detection with RADAR detection"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Ultraviolet radiation is absorbed by the atmosphere over long distances and is used in sterilisation, not RADAR.", "misconception": "Not distinguishing between different EM wave applications"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Gamma rays are extremely high-energy radiation from nuclear processes. They are not used in RADAR; they are used in medical imaging (PET scans) and cancer treatment.", "misconception": "Confusing gamma ray applications with RADAR technology"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The energy density (energy per unit volume) in an electromagnetic wave is equally divided between:", "explanation": "In an electromagnetic wave, the energy is equally shared between the electric and magnetic fields. The energy density of the electric field is uE = ½ε₀E² and that of the magnetic field is uB = B²/(2μ₀). Using E = cB and c = 1/√(μ₀ε₀), one can show that uE = uB at every point. The total energy density is u = ε₀E² = B²/μ₀.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["energy-density", "electric-field-energy", "magnetic-field-energy"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-09", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The kinetic and potential energies", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "The gravitational and electric fields", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "The amplitude and wavelength components", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "The electric and magnetic fields", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Kinetic and potential energy are concepts for mechanical waves and particles. EM waves carry energy in their electric and magnetic fields, not as kinetic/potential energy.", "misconception": "Applying mechanical wave energy concepts to electromagnetic waves"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Gravitational fields are unrelated to electromagnetic wave energy. The energy in EM waves is stored only in the oscillating electric and magnetic fields.", "misconception": "Mixing gravitational and electromagnetic concepts"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Amplitude and wavelength are properties that describe the wave, not energy reservoirs. Energy is stored in the electric and magnetic field components.", "misconception": "Confusing wave parameters with energy storage mechanisms"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A parallel plate capacitor with circular plates of radius R is being charged such that the electric field between the plates changes at the rate dE/dt. The magnetic field at a distance r (r < R) from the axis between the plates is:", "explanation": "Using the Ampere-Maxwell law: ∮B·dl = μ₀ε₀(dΦE/dt) for the region between the plates where there is no conduction current. For a circular Amperian loop of radius r (r < R), the symmetry gives B(2πr) = μ₀ε₀(πr²)(dE/dt). Therefore B = ½μ₀ε₀r(dE/dt). The magnetic field increases linearly with distance from the axis inside the capacitor, similar to the magnetic field inside a current-carrying conductor.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["ampere-maxwell-law", "displacement-current", "magnetic-field-capacitor"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-10", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "μ₀ε₀R(dE/dt)/2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "μ₀ε₀R²(dE/dt)/(2r)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "μ₀ε₀r²(dE/dt)/(2R)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "μ₀ε₀r(dE/dt)/2", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This expression uses R instead of r. For r < R, the enclosed flux depends on the area πr², not πR². The magnetic field at distance r depends on r, not R.", "misconception": "Using the full plate radius instead of the Amperian loop radius"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This expression (proportional to R²/r) describes the magnetic field for r > R (outside the plate region), not for r < R. Inside, B is proportional to r.", "misconception": "Applying the formula for the region outside the plates to the inside region"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This has an extra factor of r/R compared to the correct answer. The Amperian loop area πr² divided by 2πr gives r/2, not r²/(2R).", "misconception": "Incorrectly normalizing by the plate radius R"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "An electromagnetic wave of frequency 10 MHz propagates in vacuum. The wavelength and the magnitude of the magnetic field amplitude, given that the electric field amplitude is 60 V/m, are respectively:", "explanation": "Wavelength λ = c/f = (3 × 10⁸)/(10 × 10⁶) = 30 m. The magnetic field amplitude B₀ = E₀/c = 60/(3 × 10⁸) = 2 × 10⁻⁷ T = 200 nT. This illustrates that for EM waves, the magnetic field amplitude in SI units is much smaller than the electric field amplitude, related by the factor 1/c.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["wavelength-calculation", "E-B-ratio", "frequency-wavelength"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-11", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "30 m and 2 × 10⁻⁶ T", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "30 m and 2 × 10⁻⁷ T", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "300 m and 2 × 10⁻⁷ T", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "3 m and 2 × 10⁻⁸ T", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The wavelength 30 m is correct, but 2 × 10⁻⁶ T is off by a factor of 10. B₀ = 60/(3 × 10⁸) = 2 × 10⁻⁷ T. Check the power of 10 carefully.", "misconception": "Error in power-of-ten calculation for B₀"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "300 m would correspond to a frequency of 1 MHz, not 10 MHz. λ = c/f = 3 × 10⁸/10⁷ = 30 m.", "misconception": "Using 10⁶ instead of 10⁷ for the frequency in Hz"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "3 m corresponds to f = 100 MHz and 2 × 10⁻⁸ T is also incorrect. Both values are off by a factor of 10 from the correct answer.", "misconception": "Misplacing the decimal in both wavelength and magnetic field calculations"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "The electric field of an electromagnetic wave in vacuum is E = 6 sin(10⁷t + kx) ĵ V/m. The value of wave vector k and the direction of propagation are, respectively:", "explanation": "From the wave equation E = E₀sin(ωt + kx), ω = 10⁷ rad/s. Since c = ω/k, we get k = ω/c = 10⁷/(3 × 10⁸) = 1/30 rad/m ≈ 0.033 rad/m. The phase (ωt + kx) with a positive sign for both ω and k indicates the wave propagates in the negative x-direction (−x̂). This is because for a wave travelling in the −x direction, the phase is (ωt + kx), while for +x direction it would be (ωt − kx).", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["wave-vector", "propagation-direction", "wave-equation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-12", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "k = 1/30 rad/m, along +x direction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "k = 30 rad/m, along −x direction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "k = 1/30 rad/m, along −x direction", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "k = 10⁷ rad/m, along +x direction", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "While k = 1/30 rad/m is correct, the +kx term in the phase indicates wave propagation in the −x direction, not +x. The form sin(ωt + kx) travels in the −x̂ direction.", "misconception": "Not recognizing that sin(ωt + kx) represents a wave moving in the −x direction"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "k = 30 rad/m is incorrect; k = ω/c = 10⁷/(3 × 10⁸) = 1/30 rad/m. The direction (−x) is correct, though.", "misconception": "Inverting the k = ω/c formula to get k = c/ω"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "k = 10⁷ rad/m confuses the angular frequency ω with the wave vector k. Also, the propagation direction is −x, not +x.", "misconception": "Confusing angular frequency ω with wave number k"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): Electromagnetic waves carry energy and momentum even though they have no mass.\nReason (R): The energy of an electromagnetic wave is shared equally between its oscillating electric and magnetic fields.", "explanation": "Both the assertion and the reason are correct. EM waves carry energy (described by the Poynting vector S = E × B/μ₀) and momentum (p = U/c for energy U) despite being massless. The reason is also true: the average energy density of the electric field (½ε₀E₀²) equals that of the magnetic field (B₀²/(2μ₀)). However, the reason explains only the energy distribution, not why EM waves carry momentum. The momentum arises from the electromagnetic field itself and is related to energy by p = U/c, which is not addressed by the equal energy sharing. Therefore, R is correct but does not fully explain A (specifically the momentum part).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["em-wave-energy", "em-wave-momentum", "energy-density-equipartition"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-13", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "While both statements are true, the reason only explains energy sharing between E and B fields. It does not explain why massless EM waves carry momentum, which is a key part of the assertion.", "misconception": "Assuming any correct reason that mentions energy automatically explains momentum"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is a correct statement. The energy density of the electric field (½ε₀E²) indeed equals the energy density of the magnetic field (B²/(2μ₀)) in an EM wave.", "misconception": "Thinking energy is not equally distributed between E and B fields"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct: EM waves do carry both energy and momentum despite having no rest mass. This is experimentally verified by radiation pressure.", "misconception": "Thinking massless entities cannot carry momentum"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): Maxwell modified Ampere''s circuital law by introducing displacement current to make it consistent with the law of conservation of charge.\nReason (R): The conduction current alone was insufficient to explain the magnetic field in the region between the plates of a charging capacitor.", "explanation": "Both A and R are correct, and R is the correct explanation of A. The original Ampere''s law (∮B·dl = μ₀Ic) failed when applied to a surface passing through the gap of a charging capacitor, where no conduction current flows, yet a magnetic field exists. This inconsistency violated the continuity equation (charge conservation). Maxwell resolved this by adding the displacement current term Id = ε₀(dΦE/dt) to Ampere''s law, giving the Ampere-Maxwell law: ∮B·dl = μ₀(Ic + Id). The reason correctly identifies the specific physical situation that necessitated this modification.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["maxwell-modification", "ampere-law", "displacement-current", "charge-conservation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-14", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains the assertion. The charging capacitor scenario in R is exactly the physical situation that exposed the inconsistency in Ampere''s law and motivated Maxwell''s correction described in A.", "misconception": "Not seeing the causal link between the capacitor problem and the modification of Ampere''s law"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is correct: conduction current is indeed zero between capacitor plates during charging, yet a time-varying electric field (and hence a magnetic field) exists there.", "misconception": "Thinking conduction current flows between capacitor plates"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct: Maxwell''s addition of displacement current to Ampere''s law was specifically motivated by ensuring consistency with charge conservation.", "misconception": "Not understanding Maxwell''s historical contribution to electromagnetism"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the following types of electromagnetic radiation (Column-I) with their primary applications (Column-II):\n\nColumn-I:\nA. Infrared radiation\nB. X-rays\nC. Ultraviolet radiation\nD. Microwaves\n\nColumn-II:\n1. Cooking in microwave ovens and RADAR\n2. Medical imaging of bones and crystallography\n3. Sterilisation of water and LASIK eye surgery\n4. Night vision devices and TV remote controls", "explanation": "Infrared radiation is used in night vision equipment and TV remote controls (A→4). X-rays penetrate soft tissue but are absorbed by bones, making them ideal for medical imaging; they are also used in crystal structure determination via X-ray diffraction (B→2). Ultraviolet radiation has germicidal properties for water purification and is used in LASIK eye surgery (C→3). Microwaves are used in microwave ovens for heating food and in RADAR systems for detection and ranging (D→1).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["em-spectrum-applications", "infrared", "x-rays", "ultraviolet", "microwaves"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-15", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-4, B-3, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps X-rays and UV. X-rays are used for bone imaging (not UV), and UV is used for sterilisation (not X-rays for LASIK).", "misconception": "Confusing the medical applications of X-rays and UV"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This assigns microwave oven use to infrared and remote controls to UV. Infrared is used in remote controls, and microwaves in ovens.", "misconception": "Mixing up infrared and microwave applications"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This assigns bone imaging to infrared, which is incorrect. Infrared cannot penetrate the body to image bones; that requires X-rays.", "misconception": "Thinking infrared radiation can be used for medical bone imaging"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the following electromagnetic radiations (Column-I) with their correct source/production mechanism (Column-II):\n\nColumn-I:\nA. Radio waves\nB. X-rays\nC. Gamma rays\nD. Infrared radiation\n\nColumn-II:\n1. Vibrations of atoms and molecules (thermal agitation)\n2. Nuclear transitions and radioactive decay\n3. Oscillating electrons in an LC circuit / antenna\n4. Deceleration of high-speed electrons striking a metal target", "explanation": "Radio waves are produced by oscillating charges in LC circuits connected to antennas (A→3). X-rays are produced when fast-moving electrons are suddenly decelerated upon striking a dense metal target (Bremsstrahlung) or by inner shell electronic transitions (B→4). Gamma rays originate from transitions within the atomic nucleus and radioactive decay processes (C→2). Infrared radiation is emitted by all warm bodies due to thermal vibrations of their atoms and molecules (D→1).", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["em-wave-sources", "radio-production", "x-ray-production", "gamma-production", "infrared-production"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-16", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-3, B-2, C-4, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-4, B-3, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-1, D-2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps X-ray and gamma ray sources. X-rays come from deceleration of electrons (Bremsstrahlung), not nuclear transitions. Gamma rays come from nuclear processes.", "misconception": "Confusing X-ray and gamma ray production mechanisms"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This assigns electron deceleration to radio waves and LC circuits to X-rays, both of which are incorrect. Radio waves use LC oscillators, and X-rays use electron bombardment.", "misconception": "Reversing the production mechanisms of radio waves and X-rays"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This assigns thermal vibrations to gamma rays and nuclear decay to infrared. Gamma rays are nuclear in origin, and infrared is thermal.", "misconception": "Swapping infrared and gamma ray sources"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "All electromagnetic waves travel with the same speed in vacuum, regardless of their frequency or wavelength.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. In vacuum, all electromagnetic waves — from radio waves to gamma rays — travel at the same speed c = 3 × 10⁸ m/s = 1/√(μ₀ε₀). The speed depends only on the properties of free space (μ₀ and ε₀) and is independent of frequency, wavelength, or amplitude. This is a fundamental property that distinguishes vacuum propagation from propagation in a medium, where the speed may vary with frequency (dispersion).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["speed-of-light", "vacuum-propagation", "frequency-independence"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-17", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "In vacuum, there is no dispersion. All EM waves travel at c = 1/√(μ₀ε₀) regardless of frequency. Speed variation with frequency occurs only in material media.", "misconception": "Confusing propagation in a medium (where speed varies with frequency) with propagation in vacuum"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Electromagnetic waves are longitudinal waves, similar to sound waves.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. Electromagnetic waves are transverse waves, not longitudinal. In EM waves, the electric field E and the magnetic field B oscillate perpendicular to the direction of wave propagation. Sound waves in air are longitudinal (particles oscillate parallel to the propagation direction), but EM waves have a fundamentally different nature. The transverse nature of EM waves is confirmed by the phenomenon of polarisation.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["transverse-wave", "longitudinal-wave", "polarisation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-18", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "EM waves are transverse, not longitudinal. The E and B vectors oscillate perpendicular to the propagation direction. Polarisation of light is direct evidence of the transverse nature.", "misconception": "Confusing electromagnetic waves with sound waves; both are waves but of fundamentally different types"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for this question type.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Maxwell''s modification of Ampere''s circuital law introduces a term called displacement current, given by Id = ε₀(dΦE/dt). In the modified law, the total current enclosed is the sum of _____ current and _____ current.", "explanation": "Maxwell''s modified Ampere''s circuital law is ∮B·dl = μ₀(Ic + Id), where Ic is the conduction current (due to actual flow of charges) and Id = ε₀(dΦE/dt) is the displacement current (due to the time-varying electric field). The conduction current represents the physical movement of charge carriers through conductors, while the displacement current exists even in vacuum or dielectric regions where the electric field is changing with time.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["ampere-maxwell-law", "conduction-current", "displacement-current"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-19", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "conduction; displacement", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "conduction; induction", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "convection; displacement", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "eddy; displacement", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Induction current is the current induced by a changing magnetic flux (Faraday''s law). Maxwell''s addition to Ampere''s law was specifically the displacement current, not induction current.", "misconception": "Confusing displacement current with induced (Faraday) current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Convection current refers to charge transport by bulk motion of a fluid. The standard form of the Ampere-Maxwell law uses conduction current (flow through conductors), not convection current.", "misconception": "Confusing conduction current with convection current"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Eddy currents are induced circular currents in conductors due to changing magnetic flux. They are not part of the Ampere-Maxwell law formulation.", "misconception": "Confusing eddy currents with the conduction current in Ampere''s law"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-em-waves", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-spectrum", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A scientist is studying different regions of the electromagnetic spectrum for a research project. She needs to select appropriate EM radiation for the following task: detecting fractures in the internal bone structure of a patient without surgery.\n\nShe also notes that the wavelength of the radiation used should be comparable to interatomic spacing in crystals (about 10⁻¹⁰ m) so that the same radiation can also be used for crystal structure analysis.\n\nThe most suitable electromagnetic radiation for both purposes is:", "explanation": "X-rays are the correct choice for both applications. X-rays have wavelengths in the range of 10⁻⁸ m to 10⁻¹² m, with typical medical X-rays around 10⁻¹⁰ m. They can penetrate soft tissue but are absorbed by dense structures like bones, making them ideal for detecting bone fractures. Additionally, since their wavelength is comparable to interatomic spacings in crystals (~10⁻¹⁰ m or 1 Angstrom), they undergo diffraction when passing through crystalline materials, enabling crystal structure determination (X-ray crystallography). No other region of the EM spectrum satisfies both requirements simultaneously.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["x-rays", "medical-imaging", "crystallography", "em-spectrum-applications"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-emwave-20", "subtopic": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "topic_name": "Electromagnetic Spectrum and Wave Properties", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Ultraviolet radiation", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Gamma rays", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "X-rays", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Infrared radiation", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "UV radiation has wavelengths of 10⁻⁸ to 4 × 10⁻⁷ m, which is generally too large for crystal diffraction at interatomic spacings. UV also does not penetrate the body sufficiently to image bones.", "misconception": "Thinking UV radiation can penetrate the body to image bones"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "While gamma rays can penetrate the body, their wavelengths (< 10⁻¹² m) are much smaller than interatomic spacings, making them less suitable for standard crystal diffraction. They also pose significantly higher radiation hazards.", "misconception": "Thinking gamma rays are routinely used for bone imaging and crystallography"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Infrared radiation has wavelengths of 7 × 10⁻⁷ to 10⁻³ m, far too large for crystal diffraction and unable to penetrate the body to image bones.", "misconception": "Not recognising that infrared cannot penetrate body tissues to reveal bone structure"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b12');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The magnetic dipole moment of a bar magnet of pole strength m and magnetic length 2l is:", "explanation": "The magnetic dipole moment M of a bar magnet is defined as the product of pole strength (m) and the magnetic length (2l), i.e., M = m × 2l. The direction of M is from the south pole to the north pole inside the magnet.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["magnetic-dipole-moment", "bar-magnet", "pole-strength"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-01", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "m/2l", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "m × 2l", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "m × l", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "m²× 2l", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Dividing pole strength by length gives units of A (ampere), not A·m². The dipole moment is a product, not a ratio.", "misconception": "Confusing dipole moment formula as a ratio"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The magnetic length of the bar magnet is 2l, not l. Using l would give only half the correct magnetic moment.", "misconception": "Using half-length instead of full magnetic length"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The pole strength appears to the first power in the dipole moment formula, not squared. M = m × 2l, not m² × 2l.", "misconception": "Incorrectly squaring the pole strength"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The SI unit of magnetic dipole moment is:", "explanation": "Magnetic dipole moment M = NIA (for a current loop) or M = m × 2l (for a bar magnet). Its SI unit is A·m² (ampere-metre squared). This can be verified from M = NIA where current is in amperes and area in m².", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["magnetic-moment-unit", "SI-unit", "current-loop"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-02", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A·m²", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "A/m²", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A·m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A/m", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "A/m² is the SI unit of magnetisation (magnetic moment per unit volume), not the magnetic dipole moment itself.", "misconception": "Confusing magnetic moment with magnetisation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A·m is the unit of pole strength, not magnetic dipole moment. The moment equals pole strength times length, giving A·m × m = A·m².", "misconception": "Confusing pole strength unit with dipole moment unit"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A/m is the SI unit of magnetic field intensity H, not the magnetic dipole moment.", "misconception": "Confusing with unit of magnetic field intensity"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The angle of declination at a place is defined as the angle between:", "explanation": "Declination (or magnetic declination) is the angle between the geographic north (true north) and the magnetic north at a given location on the Earth''s surface. It is one of the three elements of Earth''s magnetism, along with dip and horizontal component.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["declination", "earth-magnetism", "geographic-north", "magnetic-north"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-03", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The magnetic meridian and the horizontal plane", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "The geographic meridian and the horizontal plane", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "The geographic meridian and the magnetic meridian", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "The magnetic axis and the rotational axis of Earth", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The angle between the magnetic meridian and the horizontal plane describes the angle of dip (inclination), not declination.", "misconception": "Confusing declination with dip"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The geographic meridian is a vertical plane; its angle with the horizontal is always 90°. Declination is measured in the horizontal plane between two meridians.", "misconception": "Confusing the definition of meridian with horizontal plane"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "While the magnetic axis is tilted relative to Earth''s rotational axis (~11.3°), declination is measured locally at each point on the surface between the two meridians.", "misconception": "Confusing global axis tilt with local declination angle"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "A current loop carrying current I and having area A behaves as a magnetic dipole with moment:", "explanation": "A planar current loop of N turns, each carrying current I and enclosing area A, acts as a magnetic dipole with magnetic moment M = NIA. For a single turn (N = 1), M = IA. The direction of M is given by the right-hand rule: curl the fingers in the direction of current, and the thumb points along M.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["current-loop", "magnetic-dipole", "magnetic-moment"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-04", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "M = I/A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "M = I²A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "M = IA²", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "M = IA", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Dividing current by area gives A/m², which is the unit of current density, not magnetic moment. The moment is the product I × A.", "misconception": "Confusing dipole moment with current density"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The current appears to the first power in M = IA. Squaring the current has no physical basis in the magnetic moment formula.", "misconception": "Incorrectly squaring the current"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The area appears to the first power. IA² would have units of A·m⁴, which is not the unit of magnetic moment (A·m²).", "misconception": "Incorrectly squaring the area"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The magnetic field on the axial line of a short bar magnet at a distance r from its centre is B₁, and the field on the equatorial line at the same distance is B₂. The ratio B₁/B₂ is:", "explanation": "For a short bar magnet (magnetic dipole), the axial field is B_axial = (μ₀/4π)(2M/r³) and the equatorial field is B_equatorial = (μ₀/4π)(M/r³). Therefore, B₁/B₂ = 2M/r³ ÷ M/r³ = 2. The axial field is always twice the equatorial field at the same distance.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["axial-field", "equatorial-field", "bar-magnet", "field-ratio"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-05", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1/2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "4", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "A ratio of 1 would mean the axial and equatorial fields are equal, but the axial field formula has an extra factor of 2 compared to the equatorial field.", "misconception": "Thinking axial and equatorial fields are equal"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "A ratio of 1/2 would mean the axial field is weaker than the equatorial field. In fact, the axial field is stronger (has the factor 2).", "misconception": "Inverting the axial-to-equatorial ratio"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "A ratio of 4 would require the axial field to have a factor of 4M instead of 2M. The correct axial field is (μ₀/4π)(2M/r³).", "misconception": "Squaring the factor of 2"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A short bar magnet of magnetic moment 0.4 J/T is placed in a uniform magnetic field of 0.16 T. The torque on the magnet when it makes an angle of 30° with the field is:", "explanation": "Torque τ = MB sinθ = 0.4 × 0.16 × sin30° = 0.4 × 0.16 × 0.5 = 0.032 N·m. The torque acts to align the magnetic moment with the external field direction.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["torque-on-dipole", "magnetic-field", "numerical-problem"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-06", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.064 N·m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.032 N·m", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.016 N·m", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.08 N·m", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.064 = 0.4 × 0.16, which omits the sin30° = 0.5 factor. The torque formula is MB sinθ, not just MB.", "misconception": "Forgetting to multiply by sinθ"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "0.016 would result from an extra factor of 1/2, perhaps from using sin30° twice. The correct calculation is 0.4 × 0.16 × 0.5 = 0.032.", "misconception": "Applying an extra factor of 1/2"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "0.08 = 0.4 × 0.2. Check the field value: it is 0.16 T, not 0.2 T.", "misconception": "Misreading the given field value"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "At a place, the horizontal component of Earth''s magnetic field is Bₕ = 0.3 G and the angle of dip is 60°. The total magnetic field of the Earth at that place is:", "explanation": "The relation between horizontal component and total field is Bₕ = B cosδ, where δ is the angle of dip. Therefore B = Bₕ/cosδ = 0.3/cos60° = 0.3/0.5 = 0.6 G. The total field B has both horizontal (Bₕ) and vertical (Bᵥ) components.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["earth-magnetic-field", "dip-angle", "horizontal-component", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-07", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.15 G", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.3 G", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.45 G", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.6 G", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.15 G = Bₕ × cos60°, which would give Bₕ × cosδ = a component, not the total field. You need to divide by cosδ, not multiply.", "misconception": "Multiplying by cosδ instead of dividing"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "0.3 G is the horizontal component itself, not the total field. The total field is always greater than or equal to the horizontal component.", "misconception": "Confusing horizontal component with total field"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "0.45 G = 0.3 × 1.5, which doesn''t follow from any correct formula. Use B = Bₕ/cos60° = 0.3/0.5 = 0.6 G.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in the division"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A bar magnet of magnetic moment M is cut into two equal halves along its length. The magnetic moment of each half is:", "explanation": "When a bar magnet is cut into two equal halves along its length (longitudinally), the pole strength of each half becomes m/2 (since the cross-section is halved), but the magnetic length remains 2l. Therefore, the magnetic moment of each half = (m/2) × 2l = M/2.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["bar-magnet-cutting", "magnetic-moment", "pole-strength"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-08", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "M/2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "M", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2M", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "M/4", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The moment cannot remain M because the pole strength is halved when the cross-section is divided. M = (m/2) × 2l = M/2.", "misconception": "Thinking that cutting along length does not change the moment"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Cutting a magnet cannot increase its magnetic moment. The total moment of all pieces cannot exceed the original moment.", "misconception": "Incorrectly doubling the moment"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "M/4 would result if both pole strength and length were halved, but longitudinal cutting only halves the pole strength, not the length.", "misconception": "Confusing longitudinal cutting with a combination of longitudinal and transverse cuts"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The potential energy of a magnetic dipole in a uniform magnetic field B is minimum when the angle between M and B is:", "explanation": "The potential energy of a magnetic dipole is U = −M·B = −MB cosθ. This is minimum when cosθ is maximum, i.e., cosθ = 1, which gives θ = 0°. At this position, the dipole is aligned with the field and is in stable equilibrium.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["potential-energy", "stable-equilibrium", "magnetic-dipole"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-09", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0°", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "90°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "180°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "45°", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "At θ = 90°, U = −MB cos90° = 0, which is neither the minimum nor the maximum value of potential energy.", "misconception": "Confusing zero energy with minimum energy"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "At θ = 180°, U = −MB cos180° = +MB, which is the maximum potential energy (unstable equilibrium), not the minimum.", "misconception": "Confusing unstable equilibrium with stable equilibrium"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "At θ = 45°, U = −MB cos45° = −MB/√2, which is less than zero but not the minimum. The minimum occurs at θ = 0° where U = −MB.", "misconception": "Choosing an arbitrary intermediate angle"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The magnetic field at a point on the axial line of a short bar magnet at a distance of 20 cm is 4 × 10⁻⁶ T. The magnetic field at a point on the equatorial line at the same distance is:", "explanation": "For a short bar magnet, B_axial = (μ₀/4π)(2M/r³) and B_equatorial = (μ₀/4π)(M/r³). Therefore B_equatorial = B_axial/2 = 4 × 10⁻⁶/2 = 2 × 10⁻⁶ T. The equatorial field is always half the axial field at the same distance from the centre.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["axial-equatorial-field", "numerical", "bar-magnet-field"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-10", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4 × 10⁻⁶ T", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2 × 10⁻⁶ T", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "8 × 10⁻⁶ T", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1 × 10⁻⁶ T", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This assumes the axial and equatorial fields are equal. The equatorial field is half the axial field at the same distance.", "misconception": "Thinking axial and equatorial fields are equal"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "8 × 10⁻⁶ T = 2 × B_axial. The equatorial field is smaller than the axial field, not larger.", "misconception": "Inverting the relationship and doubling instead of halving"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "1 × 10⁻⁶ T = B_axial/4. The correct ratio is B_eq = B_axial/2, not B_axial/4.", "misconception": "Using an incorrect division factor"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A short bar magnet has a magnetic moment of 0.48 J/T. The magnetic field at a point on the axial line at a distance of 10 cm from the centre of the magnet is: (Given: μ₀/4π = 10⁻⁷ T·m/A)", "explanation": "B_axial = (μ₀/4π)(2M/r³) = 10⁻⁷ × 2 × 0.48 / (0.1)³ = 10⁻⁷ × 0.96 / 10⁻³ = 10⁻⁷ × 960 = 9.6 × 10⁻⁵ T. Converting: 9.6 × 10⁻⁵ T = 0.96 × 10⁻⁴ T.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["axial-field", "numerical-problem", "bar-magnet-field-calculation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-11", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4.8 × 10⁻⁵ T", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2.4 × 10⁻⁵ T", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "9.6 × 10⁻⁵ T", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "19.2 × 10⁻⁵ T", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "4.8 × 10⁻⁵ T uses M/r³ instead of 2M/r³. The axial field formula has a factor of 2: B = (μ₀/4π)(2M/r³).", "misconception": "Forgetting the factor of 2 in the axial field formula"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "2.4 × 10⁻⁵ T = (μ₀/4π)(M/2r³). This uses neither the correct axial formula nor the equatorial formula.", "misconception": "Using an incorrect formula"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "19.2 × 10⁻⁵ T = 2 × 9.6 × 10⁻⁵ T. This doubles the correct answer, suggesting an error in handling powers of ten or an extra factor of 2.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in powers of 10"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "The work done in turning a magnetic needle from the direction of the horizontal component Bₕ of Earth''s field to a direction making an angle of 60° with Bₕ is W. The torque required to hold the needle in that position is:", "explanation": "Work done: W = MBₕ(1 − cos60°) = MBₕ(1 − 1/2) = MBₕ/2. Therefore MBₕ = 2W. The torque at 60° is τ = MBₕ sin60° = 2W × (√3/2) = √3 W. Hence τ = √3 W.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["torque", "work-done", "earth-field", "numerical-reasoning"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-12", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "W", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2W", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "W/2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "√3 W", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This assumes τ = W, but the torque and work done have different angular dependencies (sinθ vs 1−cosθ). You must express MBₕ from the work equation and substitute into the torque formula.", "misconception": "Equating torque directly with work done"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "2W = MBₕ is the product of moment and field, not the torque. The torque has an additional sin60° = √3/2 factor.", "misconception": "Confusing MBₕ with torque"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "W/2 would result from an incorrect formula. From MBₕ = 2W, the torque is MBₕ sin60° = 2W × √3/2 = √3 W.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in combining the expressions"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): A bar magnet is equivalent to a solenoid carrying current.\nReason (R): The magnetic field lines of a bar magnet and a current-carrying solenoid have identical patterns, with field lines emerging from one end and entering the other.", "explanation": "The assertion is correct: a bar magnet behaves identically to a solenoid in terms of its external magnetic field. The reason is also correct and directly explains the assertion: both produce the same field pattern — field lines emerge from the north pole (or the end where current flows anticlockwise) and enter the south pole (or the end where current flows clockwise). The mathematical expressions for the fields at axial and equatorial points are also identical when M = NIA.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["bar-magnet-solenoid-equivalence", "magnetic-field-pattern", "current-loop"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-13", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The identical field line pattern is exactly what establishes the equivalence of a bar magnet and a solenoid, so R is indeed the correct explanation of A.", "misconception": "Failing to see that identical field patterns establish the equivalence"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is a correct statement. Both bar magnets and solenoids produce the same dipolar field pattern outside.", "misconception": "Doubting the field pattern similarity"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is well-established in physics. A bar magnet is indeed equivalent to a solenoid, and this is a standard result in magnetism.", "misconception": "Not recognizing the bar-magnet-solenoid equivalence"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): At the magnetic equator, the angle of dip is 0° and a freely suspended magnetic needle rests horizontally.\nReason (R): At the magnetic equator, the vertical component of Earth''s magnetic field is zero.", "explanation": "The assertion is correct: at the magnetic equator, the dip angle δ = 0°, and a freely suspended needle aligns horizontally. The reason is also correct and directly explains the assertion: since Bᵥ = B sinδ, at δ = 0° we get Bᵥ = 0. With no vertical component to pull the needle downward, it rests horizontally. The entire Earth''s field at the magnetic equator is horizontal (Bₕ = B).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["magnetic-equator", "dip-angle", "vertical-component", "horizontal-component"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-14", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains the assertion: the needle rests horizontally precisely because the vertical component is zero. The causal connection is clear.", "misconception": "Not connecting zero vertical component with the horizontal resting position"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is correct. At δ = 0°, Bᵥ = B sin0° = 0. This is a direct consequence of the dip angle being zero.", "misconception": "Incorrectly thinking the vertical component is non-zero at the magnetic equator"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct and verifiable. At the magnetic equator, dip is indeed 0° and the needle does rest horizontally.", "misconception": "Confusing magnetic equator with geographic equator and doubting the assertion"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the elements of Earth''s magnetism in Column I with their definitions in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Declination\nB. Angle of dip (Inclination)\nC. Horizontal component Bₕ\nD. Vertical component Bᵥ\n\nColumn II:\n1. B sinδ, where δ is the dip angle\n2. The angle between the geographic meridian and the magnetic meridian\n3. B cosδ, where δ is the dip angle\n4. The angle between the total Earth''s field and the horizontal direction in the magnetic meridian", "explanation": "Declination is the angle between geographic and magnetic meridians → A-2. Dip is the angle between the total field vector and the horizontal in the magnetic meridian → B-4. The horizontal component is Bₕ = B cosδ → C-3. The vertical component is Bᵥ = B sinδ → D-1.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["earth-magnetism-elements", "declination", "dip", "horizontal-vertical-components"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-15", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-2, B-3, C-4, D-1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps A and B. Declination is the angle between meridians (definition 2), while dip is the angle of the total field with horizontal (definition 4).", "misconception": "Confusing declination with dip"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This swaps C and D. The horizontal component uses cosδ (C-3), and the vertical component uses sinδ (D-1), not the other way around.", "misconception": "Interchanging sinδ and cosδ for horizontal and vertical components"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This assigns definition 3 (B cosδ) to dip, but dip is an angle (definition 4), not a field component.", "misconception": "Confusing the dip angle with a field component formula"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the physical situations in Column I with the correct magnetic field expressions or properties in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Axial point of a magnetic dipole (far field)\nB. Equatorial point of a magnetic dipole (far field)\nC. Neutral point when N-pole points north (bar magnet on table)\nD. Neutral point when N-pole points south (bar magnet on table)\n\nColumn II:\n1. Located on the axial line of the magnet\n2. (μ₀/4π)(M/r³), directed opposite to M\n3. Located on the equatorial line of the magnet\n4. (μ₀/4π)(2M/r³), directed along M", "explanation": "The axial field at far distance is (μ₀/4π)(2M/r³), directed along M → A-4. The equatorial field at far distance is (μ₀/4π)(M/r³), directed opposite to M → B-2. When the N-pole of a bar magnet points geographic north, the magnet''s field opposes Earth''s field on the equatorial line, so neutral points are on the equatorial line → C-3. When the N-pole points south, neutral points lie on the axial line → D-1.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["axial-equatorial-field", "neutral-points", "bar-magnet-earth-field"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-16", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps C and D. When N-pole points north, the axial field adds to Earth''s field and the equatorial field opposes it, so neutral points are on the equatorial line (C-3, not C-1).", "misconception": "Confusing which line has neutral points for N-pole pointing north vs south"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This swaps A and B. The axial field has the factor 2 in the numerator and is along M; the equatorial field has factor 1 and is opposite to M.", "misconception": "Interchanging axial and equatorial field formulas"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is identical to option A with C and D swapped from the correct answer. Neutral points for N-pole north are on the equatorial line (perpendicular bisector), not the axial line.", "misconception": "Confusing the location of neutral points"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The magnetic field lines of a bar magnet form continuous closed loops, emerging from the north pole outside the magnet and running from south to north inside the magnet.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. Unlike electric field lines, magnetic field lines always form continuous closed loops. Outside the magnet, they go from north pole to south pole. Inside the magnet, they continue from south pole to north pole, completing the loop. This is a consequence of Gauss''s law for magnetism (∇·B = 0), which states that magnetic monopoles do not exist.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["magnetic-field-lines", "closed-loops", "gauss-law-magnetism"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-17", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Magnetic field lines do form closed loops. This is a fundamental difference between electric field lines (which start and end on charges) and magnetic field lines (which have no starting or ending points because magnetic monopoles don''t exist).", "misconception": "Confusing magnetic field lines with electric field lines that do not form closed loops"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The geographic north pole of the Earth and the magnetic north pole of the Earth are located at the same point.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. The geographic north pole (true north, defined by Earth''s rotational axis) and the magnetic north pole (where the Earth''s magnetic field points vertically downward) are NOT at the same location. The magnetic north pole is offset from the geographic north pole by about 11.3°. In fact, the Earth''s magnetic south pole is located near the geographic north pole (since field lines enter the Earth near the geographic north).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["geographic-pole", "magnetic-pole", "earth-magnetism"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-18", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The geographic and magnetic poles do not coincide. The angle between the geographic meridian and magnetic meridian (declination) varies across the globe, precisely because these poles are at different locations.", "misconception": "Assuming geographic and magnetic north poles are at the same location"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option is not applicable for true/false questions.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "At a place where the angle of dip is 45°, the horizontal and vertical components of Earth''s magnetic field are _____.", "explanation": "When the angle of dip δ = 45°, we have Bₕ = B cos45° = B/√2 and Bᵥ = B sin45° = B/√2. Since Bₕ = Bᵥ, the horizontal and vertical components are equal in magnitude. Also, tanδ = Bᵥ/Bₕ = tan45° = 1, confirming Bᵥ = Bₕ.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["dip-angle", "horizontal-component", "vertical-component", "equal-components"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-19", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Bₕ = 2Bᵥ (horizontal is twice the vertical)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Bᵥ = 2Bₕ (vertical is twice the horizontal)", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Equal in magnitude (Bₕ = Bᵥ)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Bₕ = 0 and Bᵥ = B (only vertical component exists)", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Bₕ = 2Bᵥ would require tanδ = 1/2, giving δ ≈ 26.6°, not 45°. At δ = 45°, tanδ = 1, so Bₕ = Bᵥ.", "misconception": "Incorrect trigonometric evaluation at 45°"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Bᵥ = 2Bₕ would require tanδ = 2, giving δ ≈ 63.4°. At 45° dip, both components are equal.", "misconception": "Confusing 45° dip with a steeper dip angle"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Bₕ = 0 occurs only at the magnetic poles where δ = 90°. At δ = 45°, both horizontal and vertical components are non-zero and equal.", "misconception": "Confusing 45° dip with 90° dip (at the poles)"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-magnetic-effects", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-mag-dipole", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "A geologist is surveying a region using a dip circle. At a particular location, she measures the angle of dip to be 30° and the horizontal component of Earth''s magnetic field to be 0.36 G. She needs to determine the total magnetic field strength and the vertical component at this location.\n\nWhat is the vertical component Bᵥ of Earth''s magnetic field at this location?", "explanation": "Given: δ = 30°, Bₕ = 0.36 G. Using the relation tanδ = Bᵥ/Bₕ, we get Bᵥ = Bₕ tanδ = 0.36 × tan30° = 0.36 × (1/√3) = 0.36/1.732 ≈ 0.208 G. Alternatively, Bᵥ = 0.36/√3 = 0.12√3 G ≈ 0.208 G. The total field B = Bₕ/cosδ = 0.36/cos30° = 0.36/(√3/2) = 0.72/√3 ≈ 0.416 G.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["earth-magnetism", "dip-angle", "vertical-component", "scenario-based", "numerical"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-magmat-dipole-20", "subtopic": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "topic_name": "Magnetic Dipole and Torque", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.36 G", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.72 G", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.18 G", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.12√3 G ≈ 0.208 G", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "0.36 G is the horizontal component, not the vertical component. With a dip of 30°, the vertical component is smaller than the horizontal component since tan30° < 1.", "misconception": "Confusing horizontal component with vertical component"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "0.72 G = 2 × Bₕ. This might result from using an incorrect formula. The correct relation is Bᵥ = Bₕ tan30° = 0.36 × (1/√3) ≈ 0.208 G.", "misconception": "Using an incorrect multiplying factor"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "0.18 G = Bₕ/2 = Bₕ × sin30°, but the correct formula is Bᵥ = Bₕ tanδ, not Bₕ sinδ.", "misconception": "Using sinδ instead of tanδ in the formula for Bᵥ"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b12');

